{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T03:14:33.904204", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis Routes to Valine\nSeveral pathways have been proposed for abiotic valine formation. Classical Miller\u2013Urey\u2013type spark\u2010discharge experiments with a reducing gas mixture (H\u2082, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082O) generate dozens of amino acids; reanalysis of Miller\u2019s original samples detected valine (and its diastereomer isovaline) among dozens of products[1]. In these electric\u2010discharge experiments, the atmosphere is heated to ~800\u20131200\u202f\u00b0C in brief sparks and cooled, giving rise to Strecker\u2010type chemistry (see below). Valine is only a minor product under such conditions (glycine/alanine dominate), but its presence shows branched amino acids can arise from simple feedstocks[1].\nThe canonical Strecker synthesis is another obvious route: an aldehyde or ketone reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN to give an \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to an amino acid. For valine this requires isobutyraldehyde (2\u2011methylpropanal, (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) as the carbonyl. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) noted that \u201cisobutyraldehyde is the Strecker precursor to valine\u201d, while \u03b1\u2011ketoisovaleric acid (the transamination product of valine) also participates in these networks[2]. In practice, Strecker routes likely require high pH (because NH\u2083 has pK_aH\u22489.2)[3] and concentrated cyanide. Recent work shows that diamidophosphate (DAP) can promote Strecker syntheses at neutral pH, giving \u201cN\u2011phosphoro\u2011aminonitriles\u201d in high yield (73\u2013quantitative) from simple aldehydes and HCN[3]. By analogy, DAP or related salts could enable valine formation from isobutyraldehyde under mild conditions. However, Strecker reactions select poorly among substrates: Miller & Schlesinger found pantoic acid (from isobutyraldehyde) forms along with glycine, alanine and GABA without selectivity[4]. In summary, Strecker chemistry from isobutyraldehyde\u2009+\u2009NH\u2083\u2009+\u2009HCN is a plausible route to valine via valinonitrile, but it hinges on prebiotic supply of isobutyraldehyde (see Precursors).\nA modern variant is the cyanosulfidic photochemistry first detailed by Patel et al. (2015). In this scheme, HCN is reductively homologated under UV irradiation in the presence of H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox catalysts to build up carbon skeletons. Starting from simpler sugars and cyanide, the chemistry yields \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile precursors of valine (and leucine) via multi\u2010step dark/photochemical cycles. For example, glyceraldehyde and its acetone byproduct are converted (via \u03b1-hydroxythioamides and thioamides) into the cyanohydrin intermediate 26; subsequent addition of NH\u2083 then gives the valine aminonitrile (27)[5][6]. In Patel et al.\u2019s experiments, this 4-step homologation (Fig. 1b) proceeded in ~42% yield of 27[7]. Crucially, this route requires UV irradiation and H\u2082S as reductant; copper sulfide minerals (e.g. cuprous sulfide) can supply Cu(I) and generate HS\u207b from cyanide[8][9]. Thus the cyanosulfidic pathway converges on valine via a Strecker\u2010like aminonitrile, but built up in situ from HCN, small sugars and sulfide.\nA third route is metal\u2010catalyzed reductive amination of keto acids. Kaur et al. (2024) showed that under mild (22\u202f\u00b0C, pH 8) conditions, H\u2082 gas can reduce \u03b1\u2011ketoacids in the presence of NH\u2083 and metal catalysts to yield amino acids[10]. In that work, Ni nanoparticles (and even Ni-bearing meteorite powder) catalyzed H\u2082\u2010driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (the \u03b1\u2011keto acid of valine) into valine[10]. The reactions used 5 bar H\u2082, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, pH 7\u20138 water and 72 h reaction time; with Ni catalysts the combined yield of amino+hydroxy acids was 6\u201384% (valine was one product)[10]. (A Pd catalyst gave higher yields but with >5:1 selectivity of amino acid over the competing \u03b1\u2011hydroxy acid[10].) This \u201cmetabolism\u2010like\u201d hydrogenation network suggests alkaline hydrothermal vent settings (rich in H\u2082 and Ni\u2010Fe minerals) could produce valine by reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.\nOther proposed routes are less studied. For example, generalized formose-type chemistry (polymerization of H\u2082CO) can produce various aldehydes and sugars, but it is not known to yield branched C\u2083 aldehydes efficiently. Similarly, Fischer\u2013Tropsch synthesis on metal sulfides tends to give linear acids (acetate, pyruvate, etc.) rather than branched amino acids. Miller\u2013Urey experiments with added sulfide or formamide have been suggested to improve yields of certain amino acids, but specific valine yields are rarely reported. In summary, the main validated pathways to prebiotic valine are: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde[2], (2) photochemical homologation of HCN[5], (3) H\u2082\u2010driven reductive amination of \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate[10], and (4) complex spark\u2010discharge mixtures[1].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors\nAll known routes rely on larger precursors that embody valine\u2019s branched C\u2083 skeleton. In Strecker chemistry the key intermediate is isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO), which condenses with NH\u2083 and HCN to give valine\u2019s aminonitrile (valinonitrile). Miller & Schlesinger explicitly identified isobutyraldehyde as \u201cthe Strecker precursor to valine\u201d[2]. Similarly, \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate (3\u2011methyl\u20112\u2011oxobutanoate) is the immediate precursor in reductive amination routes; it can arise by transamination of valine or by a prior homologation (e.g. as a product of a reductive aldol sequence). In the cyanosulfidic pathway, smaller precursors feed into acetone and acetone derivatives: glyceraldehyde (a C\u2083 sugar) dehydrates/decays partly to dihydroxyacetone (acetone-3, C\u2083) and acetone itself, which then is converted (via thioamide intermediates) to cyanohydrin 26. The \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (formed by NH\u2083 addition) is the penultimate precursor to valine[5]. In all cases the ultimate atom sources are simple C, N, H compounds: HCN, HCHO, NH\u2083, H\u2082, CO\u2082 etc. The key branch\u2011forming steps thus involve either homologation (adding \u2013CH\u2082\u2013 units via HCN chemistry) or decarboxylation of longer keto acids.\nOther precursors can play roles. For example, formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde may polymerize on mineral surfaces to give higher aldols, but branched products are not favored thermodynamically. In the cyanosulfidic route, acetone originates from initial photoredox reduction of dihydroxyacetone (which itself comes from photoredox of glyceraldehyde). Thus dihydroxyacetone (acetone-2) and acetone (acetone-3) are intermediates en route to the valine nitrile[5]. Hydroxylated thioamides (e.g. compounds 24,28 in Patel et al.) and nitriles (26,30) appear transiently in that scheme. Importantly, ammonia (NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a) is a branch precursor (necessary for the \u2013NH\u2082 group in valine) and cyanide (HCN/CN\u207b) provides the \u2013CN unit in aminonitriles; their availability dictates each route\u2019s feasibility. In short, isobutyraldehyde and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the largest building blocks needed, while HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082, formaldehyde, and small sugars are the ubiquitous feedstocks from which these can be assembled.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions\nStrecker Synthesis (Chemical Condensation): Isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valine aminonitrile \u2192 valine after hydrolysis. Mechanistically, the aldehyde first forms an imine with NH\u2083, then CN\u207b adds to give the aminonitrile, which on water\u2010catalyzed hydrolysis yields valine. Conditions reported are aqueous, often neutral\u2010to-basic pH (~8\u201310) because free NH\u2083 is needed[3]. Miller (1993) showed that adding metal salts (Mg\u00b2\u207a, Ca\u00b2\u207a, transition metals) catalyzes reactions of \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) under Strecker-like conditions[2]. Diamidophosphate (DAP) enables the \u201cStrecker\u201d at neutral pH by temporarily masking NH\u2083 and activating HCN/aldehyde[3]. Typical yields depend on concentration and pH; classical Strecker gives roughly 10\u201350% conversion to aminonitrile for favorable substrates, although yields for valine\u2019s nitrile specifically are not routinely reported. One experimental metric: Powner et al. achieved 73\u2013quantitative% yield of N-phosphoro-aminonitriles at pH 7 from simple aldehydes[3] (analogous conditions should work for isobutyraldehyde). After Strecker, heating or acid can hydrolyze the nitrile to the amino acid. The environment is typically a shallow pool or evaporating basin where HCN and NH\u2083 concentrate and ammonia is deprotonated (e.g. volcanic lakes or drying geothermal ponds).\nCyanosulfidic Photoredox (Patel et al. 2015): This multi-step mechanism uses UV light and sulfide. Key steps (Fig. 1b in [5]) are:\n\u2022\tAddition of HCN to ketones: Acetone (formed from glyceraldehyde/dihydroxyacetone) reacts with HCN to give cyanohydrin 23. This is typically reversible, but under the \u201cdark\u201d addition of HS\u207b it converts to an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide (compound 24)[11].\n\u2022\tPhotoreduction: UV light with H\u2082S reductant converts the hydroxylthioamide to a thioamide (25) and further to an aldehyde (byloss of S and H insertion). Continuing UV in H\u2082S + HCN traps the aldehyde as cyanohydrin 26[12].\n\u2022\tAmmonia addition: Finally, NH\u2083 adds to cyanohydrin 26 to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (valine precursor)[13].\nConditions were aqueous, UV irradiation (\u2248254 nm or broad UV), presence of H\u2082S (hydrosulfide), phosphate buffer, and catalytic Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on sulfide minerals. Patel et al. carried out these steps in sequence (often with intermediate purification) under room-temperature conditions. Table 1 in [5] shows that converting 26\u219227 gave 42% yield in one step. In practice, overall yields for each homologation step were on the order of tens of percent[5]. Side products include simpler amino acids (alanine, glycine) from parallel pathways, but valine\u2019s pathway was clearly observed. This chemistry is most plausible in sunlit terrestrial ponds with abundant HCN and HS\u207b (e.g. sulfidic lakes or streams after meteorite impacts[14]).\nReductive Amination (Hydrogenation): Kaur et al. demonstrated a straightforward mechanism: an \u03b1-keto acid is hydrogenated and aminated to give the amino acid. For valine, 2-oxoisovalerate + H\u2082 + NH\u2084\u207a \u2192 valine + H\u2082O. This is essentially the reverse of branched amino acid dehydrogenases. They used metallic catalysts (10 mol% Ni or Pd on support) or Ni-rich meteorite powder, 5 bar H\u2082 gas, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, at pH 8 and 22\u202f\u00b0C[15]. After 72 h, Ni catalysts yielded mixtures of valine and a mixture of hydroxy acids (from partial reduction of the ketoacid); overall conversion was 6\u201384% (depending on catalyst), typically ~50% with Ni[10]. Pd catalysts gave higher yields (~80%) and >5:1 selectivity for amino vs hydroxy acids. No reaction occurred without catalyst[10]. Thus, mild alkaline hydrothermal fluids (cool vents or mixing zones) rich in H\u2082 and NH\u2083 could produce valine from keto precursors with Ni/Fe minerals. Yields are high if the ketoacid is available, and the chemistry tolerates neutral to slightly alkaline pH and ambient to moderate temperature.\nSpark and Miller-type Experiments: In these, a gaseous mixture (e.g. 50% CH\u2084, 20% NH\u2083, 30% H\u2082O vapor) is discharged by spark. Products include amino acids, cyanides, and hydrocarbons. Early analyses found glycine, alanine, aspartic acid in mg yield per liter; valine was present at trace levels. Johnson et al. (2009) reported dozens of amino acids, including valine and isovaline, in Miller\u2019s 1953 samples[1]. Quantitative yields for valine weren\u2019t given, but glycine was tens of \u03bcg/mL in the total liquid. Such discharges represent surface/atmospheric conditions (lightning or volcanism).\nEach route has trade-offs in yield and selectivity. Strecker is efficient for many amino acids in one pot, but requires free NH\u2083 (or masked NH\u2083 like DAP) and yields mixtures (glycine, alanine often dominate). Cyanosulfidic chemistry is selective but complex, needing sequential addition of reagents and UV exposure[16]. Hydrogenation gives good selectivity but needs specific keto precursors. In all cases, yields of valine are modest (single-digit to tens of percent per step) and accompanied by by-products.\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces\nMineral surfaces are central to many proposed valine syntheses. Nickel and Iron Sulfides: Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user famously invoked NiS/FeS as \u201cproto-enzymes.\u201d In Kaur et al.\u2019s experiments, Ni dispersed on silica or FeNi meteorite powder was required[15]. Specifically, Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) and ground Aletai meteorite (18 mol% Ni) were used as H\u2082 hydrogenation catalysts[15]. Natural analogs include pentlandite [(Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088] or mackinawite (FeS) in hydrothermal vents, which can reduce CO\u2082 and nitriles. Copper Sulfides: Patel et al. note that Cu\u2082S or covellite could catalyze their photochemical cycles. Cu(I) forms (e.g. chalcopyrite) can facilitate HCN cross-coupling and photoredox; indeed, Cu(I)/Cu(II) on sulfides is a photosensitizer that drives the HCN homologation with H\u2082S[9]. Cu(II) minerals (malachite) might also transiently form, but CuS is key. Pyrite/Greigite: Iron sulfide (FeS\u2082, Fe\u2083S\u2084) surfaces have been shown to catalyze reduction of nitriles and CO\u2082. While specific studies on valine are lacking, FeS/FeS\u2082 could (by analogy to acetate/pyruvate synthesis) facilitate C\u2013N bond formation or HCN polymerization.\nMontmorillonite and Clays: Smectite clays like montmorillonite can concentrate organics and catalyze certain condensations (e.g. amino acid polymerization). They may help align isobutyraldehyde, HCN and NH\u2083 for Strecker synthesis in drying pools, although direct evidence for valine-specific catalysis is scarce. Experiments have shown clay surfaces strongly adsorb amino acids (including valine)[17], which could assist in concentrating them but can also inhibit reactivity.\nOther Minerals: Zn\u00b2\u207a and other divalent cations accelerate Strecker steps (by stabilizing imines)[2]. Transition\u2010metal phosphides (schreibersite, (Fe,Ni)\u2083P) can hydrolyze to yield phosphate and reduced phosphorus (P\u2083\u207b) which may activate feedstocks, though their role for valine is indirect. NiFe alloys (from meteorites) and iron oxides (magnetite, hematite) also feature in origin-of-life scenarios, but no specific valine synthesis has been demonstrated on them.\nIn summary, Ni/Fe sulfide minerals (present in vents and meteorites) and copper sulfides (in terrestrial Hadean environments) are the main catalysts identified for valine precursors[15][9]. Many origin-of-life studies emphasize these minerals for amino\u2010acid chemistry, so they likely played a role in any prebiotic valine formation.\nExperimental Evidence\n\u2022\tMiller\u2013Urey experiments: Stanley Miller\u2019s 1953 spark\u2011discharge (CH\u2084\u2013NH\u2083\u2013H\u2082O) produced amino acids. Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed original residues and found valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids[1]. This confirms branched amino acids can form abiotically. Glycine/alanine dominated quantitatively, so valine\u2019s yield was low (trace ppm in solution), but its presence is significant.\n\u2022\tStrecker experiments: Although classic Strecker syntheses were developed in the lab (mid-19th century), application to prebiotic chemistry was discussed by Or\u00f3 and others. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) showed that heating isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN (in formamide/water) yields pantoic acid, noting isobutyraldehyde\u2019s connection to valine[2]. They reported that metal salts (Mg, Ca, Fe, Co) catalyze \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reactions, implying Fe/Ni minerals could assist Strecker routes. Quantitative yields for valine itself were not given, but amino acids including glycine/alanine were coproduced[4].\n\u2022\tCyanosulfidic photochemistry: Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) explicitly demonstrated steps toward valine. They showed that UV irradiation of acetone cyanohydrin derivatives with NH\u2083 yields valine aminonitrile 27, with ~42% isolated yield from intermediate 26[5]. The full cascade from glyceraldehyde to 27 was mapped out (Table 1) and validated by NMR and GC (see supplementary figs in [5]). This is strong proof-of-concept for the \u201cHCN + H\u2082S + UV\u201d pathway.\n\u2022\tReductive amination (Kaur et al., 2024, Chem): Kaur and coworkers reported that Ni or meteorite catalysts convert six \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) to amino acids at room temp and pH 8. They measured yields by NMR: with Ni, valine (from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) appeared at ~10\u201350% yield alongside hydroxy acids[10]. Using Pd gave even higher amino acid yields (80\u201390%). Control experiments (no metal, no H\u2082) gave no reaction[10]. This demonstrates that H\u2082-driven amino acid formation is experimentally viable.\n\u2022\tPHOTOCHEMICAL AND OTHER LAB STUDIES: Although not specific to valine, many \u201cMiller\u2010type\u201d experiments under UV or spark conditions produce alanine and often minor valine. For example, glow-discharge on H\u2082\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082 can make amino acids if NH\u2083 or N-containing species are added. No single experiment has targeted valine exclusively, but dozens of studies (reviewed in Patel 2015, Cleaves 2018, Hud 2020) show that branched amino acids can form in mixtures of simple precursors under plausible prebiotic conditions[1][2]. Yields tend to be lower than for glycine/alanine, often <1%.\nIn sum, laboratory evidence supports every step in the proposed pathways. Aminonitriles analogous to valine\u2019s have been isolated; dehydration/hydrolysis steps are well understood; and catalysts (Ni, Cu, Zn) accelerate relevant bond formations. Quantitative data: for Strecker, reported aminonitrile yields from simple aldehydes (e.g. glycine precursor) exceed 50% under optimized conditions[3]; for the photochemical chain, intermediate yields ranged 40\u201370% per step[7]; for reductive amination, valine yields up to ~50% in multi-step mixtures[10]. Although absolute yields vary widely with conditions, these experiments confirm that valine can be synthesized from prebiotic feedstocks.\nEnvironmental Context\nDifferent steps favor different prebiotic environments. Tidal Flats/Evaporitic Basins: Sites with alternating wet/dry cycles concentrate salts and organics (HCN, aldehydes). Sutherland\u2019s cyanosulfidic chemistry is envisioned in shallow \u201cponds\u201d fed by streams carrying ferrocyanide salts[14]. UV light drives key reactions (cyanohydrin formation, photoreduction) in sunlit pools. Sequential merging of streams (with different chemistries) helps deliver reagents stepwise[18][16]. Meteorite impacts could create localized HCN and phosphate (via schreibersite), which upon dissolution feed these basins[14].\nAlkaline Hydrothermal Vents: These are rich in H\u2082, NH\u2083 (from serpentinization or volcanism), and metal sulfides (FeS, NiS). The reductive amination route is most plausible here. Temperatures of 50\u2013150\u202f\u00b0C and high pressures (1\u2013100 bar) are typical. Kaur et al. used mild conditions (22\u202f\u00b0C, 5 bar H\u2082) to mimic cold vent effluent; higher T (50\u2013100\u202f\u00b0C) might even accelerate reactions further. Confinement in mineral pores (e.g. green rust chimneys) could concentrate reactants. Some have suggested fumarolic volcanoes (with H\u2082S) for the photoredox steps as well, but UV is lacking in deep vents.\nAtmosphere and Lightning: Early Earth volcanic eruptions and lightning would produce HCN and small aldehydes in the atmosphere. The classic Miller setup mimics this, with electrical discharge providing energy. Rainout deposits the amino acids into pools. Johnson et al. note: \u201can intense barrage of lightning\u2026 accompanied by eruptions, followed by precipitation\u201d could produce a prebiotic soup containing valine[19]. HCN generated in the atmosphere could also dissolve in oceans or lakes (e.g. forming ferrocyanides[14]), seeding other chemistries.\nIce and Cryoenvironments: Cold regions (ice eutectics) can concentrate solutes and allow slow chemistry. Some experiments show HCN polymerization or amino acid stability in ice, but branched amino acid synthesis specifically has not been demonstrated in ice. Nonetheless, impacts on icy bodies (comets) and icy terrains may be minor sources of amino acids that include valine.\nIn practice, a combination is likely: for example, UV\u2010irradiated streams might produce valine nitrile which is then washed into geothermal pools where hydrolysis and further chemistry occur. The fact that valine is found in meteorites (along with other amino acids) suggests that similar chemistries occurred on asteroid parent bodies, which can be seen as analogs of hydrothermal or UV\u2010irradiated environments.\nOpen Questions and Challenges\nDespite these advances, many aspects remain unresolved. Source of the Branched Precursor: All known routes require C\u2084 or C\u2085 precursors (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate). It is unclear how these were supplied prebiotically. Acetone formation (needed in Patel\u2019s route) is shown, but obtaining sufficient isobutyraldehyde in early Earth settings is speculative. Similarly, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate must arise from prior synthesis (e.g. reductive aldol of glyoxylate and ketone) or contamination. Identifying an efficient abiotic source of these specific precursors is a key gap.\npH and Chemical Constraints: Traditional Strecker synthesis requires high pH or masked ammonia[3], which may not coincide with HCN stability (HCN is volatile at high pH). While DAP circumvents this, DAP itself must be generated (likely from wet-dry cycling of meteorite phosphides). Cyanosulfidic chemistry demands careful timing of reagents (HCN, H\u2082S, phosphate)[16]; how natural environments could orchestrate these pulses (stream merger vs. single\u2010pot) is debated.\nCompetition and Side Reactions: Valine synthesis competes with formation of simpler amino acids, nitriles and polymeric organics. In Miller-type mixtures, glycine/alanine dominate, and branched amino acids are minor. In photochemical networks, many intermediates are lost to side products (e.g. elemental sulfur, HCN polymers). Thus yields of valine in realistic mixtures may be very low, raising the question of whether it would have reached useful concentrations. Some studies have noted poor selectivity (e.g. pantoic vs. glycine formation[4]).\nThermodynamics and Kinetics: The free-energy landscape of these reactions is not fully mapped. For example, the Strecker condensation of a ketone (isobutyraldehyde) with NH\u2083 and HCN is less favorable than for an aldehyde (like glyoxylate). Reductive amination of keto acids is exergonic with H\u2082, but if H\u2082 is limited the reaction may stall. Detailed thermodynamic data for branched amino acid formation under early Earth conditions are sparse.\nHomochirality: All prebiotic routes produce racemic valine (as seen in meteorites). The origin of L-valine in biology is separate (likely via chiral catalysts or selective degradation). However, the lack of any enantiomeric bias in these syntheses is a challenge for explaining life\u2019s L\u2010preference. (Isovaline in meteorites shows some L\u2010excess, but valine is usually racemic, suggesting even if delivered, an enantiomeric excess likely arose later.)\nExperimental Limitations: Many proposed steps have been shown in isolation or under idealized lab conditions. It remains to combine these steps in more realistic, multi-step \u201cone-pot\u201d simulations. For example, no experiment has yet converted HCN all the way to valine in a single simulated pond. Also, geological plausibility (e.g. continuous H\u2082 supply or UV flux) needs further assessment.\nIn summary, the biggest challenges are supplying the correct carbon backbone (branch points) and integrating steps under a coherent early Earth scenario. While several credible pathways to valine exist[2][5][10], no single route is fully proven in a fully prebiotic setting. Resolving these open questions\u2014especially precursor availability and yield limitations\u2014will be crucial for understanding valine\u2019s origin on the prebiotic Earth.\nSources: Peer-reviewed studies (Miller & Schlesinger 1993[2]; Patel et al. 2015[5]; Kaur et al. 2024[10]; Powner et al. 2019[3]; Johnson et al. 2009[1]) and origin-of-life reviews.[5][10][3][2][1]\n \n[1] [19] The Diversity of the Original Prebiotic Soup: Re-analyzing the Original Miller-Urey Spark Discharge Experiments - ADS\nhttps://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2009OLEB...39..240J/abstract\n[2] [4] Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid, pantothenic acid, and the composition of coenzyme A - PubMed\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11536535/\n[3] Selective prebiotic synthesis of phosphoroaminonitriles and aminothioamides in neutral water | Communications Chemistry\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s42004-019-0124-5?error=cookies_not_supported&code=ab3c0682-3751-4eed-af88-0eb76a495a8b\n[5] [6] [7] [8] [9] [11] [12] [13] [14] [16] [18]  Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\n[10] [15]  A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7616004/\n[17] The adsorption of valine on cation-exchanged montmorillonites - DOI\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.clay.2003.08.004\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network that integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine. The network topology is excellent with 18 molecules, 16 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points. Literature alignment is strong: the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic pathway, Kaur et al. reductive amination, Miller-Schlesinger Strecker synthesis, and Johnson et al. spark-discharge chemistry are all properly represented and cited. The environmental flow (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) is well-structured.\n\nHowever, three reactions have significant chemical issues: (1) rxn_006 (pyruvate\u2192acetone) is incorrect\u2014pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde, not acetone; (2) rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is a massive oversimplification of a multi-step biosynthetic pathway with no prebiotic precedent as a single reaction; (3) rxn_014 (Fischer-Tropsch \u2192 isobutyraldehyde) overstates FTT selectivity for branched products, which the literature itself acknowledges is unlikely. These errors affect 6 of 10 pathways.\n\nDespite these issues, pathways P1 and P6 (the cyanosulfidic routes) remain chemically sound and well-supported, achieving valine through literature-validated Patel et al. chemistry. The network successfully reaches the target through multiple valid routes. Mineral catalysts should be more explicitly specified for surface reactions (Cu sulfides for photoreduction, borate for formose). Overall, this is a strong network that would benefit from fixing the three problematic reactions.\n- Issues: ['This pathway is critically undermined by rxn_006: thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) yields acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) + CO2, NOT acetone (CH3COCH3). Acetone requires a C3 + C3 condensation (e.g., via acetoacetate decarboxylation) or a completely different mechanism. This fundamental chemical error invalidates the pathway as written. Downstream steps from acetone onward are fine.', 'Appealingly short, and the terminal reductive amination (rxn_013) is directly supported by Kaur et al. 2024. However, rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is a major oversimplification. Biosynthetically, this requires multiple enzymatic steps: pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 2,3-dihydroxyisovalerate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. As a single prebiotic reaction, it lacks experimental support. The C3 + C1 \u2192 C5 branched product with no intermediates is chemically implausible in one step.', \"An elegant short pathway. The Strecker and hydrolysis steps are well-supported. However, rxn_014 (Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of isobutyraldehyde from CO + H2) is problematic: FTT synthesis on metal sulfides typically favors linear products (methanol, acetate, formate, linear alkanes/alcohols), and branched C4 aldehydes are not favored products. The literature notes that 'Fischer-Tropsch synthesis on metal sulfides tends to give linear acids rather than branched amino acids.' Specificity for isobutyraldehyde is not experimentally demonstrated.\", 'Biologically elegant transamination pathway, with rxn_015 (reductive amination to alanine) and rxn_016 (transamination) both well-precedented. However, the pathway inherits the critical weakness of rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate). Transamination (rxn_016) requires pyridoxal-type cofactors or metal ion catalysis prebiotically, which should be specified. The regeneration of pyruvate in rxn_016 is a nice autocatalytic feature.', 'The convergent concept is excellent\u2014two independent routes to acetone merging at rxn_007. However, the pyruvate decarboxylation arm (rxn_006) is chemically incorrect (pyruvate gives acetaldehyde, not acetone), so only the cyanosulfidic arm (via rxn_005) actually contributes valid acetone. This removes the convergence benefit.', 'Good convergence concept with two routes to isobutyraldehyde (cyanosulfidic photoreduction and Fischer-Tropsch). The cyanosulfidic arm is stronger; the FTT arm (rxn_014) is weakly supported for branched products. The Strecker + hydrolysis conclusion is solid.', 'Hybrid pathway that would convert \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to isobutyraldehyde for Strecker synthesis. The concept is interesting but rxn_012 remains the bottleneck. Also unclear how \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is converted to isobutyraldehyde\u2014this reduction/decarboxylation step seems to be missing from the explicit reactions.', 'Ambitious autocatalytic cycle concept linking cyanosulfidic valine production with transamination recycling. While conceptually appealing for proto-metabolic networks, it inherits weaknesses from rxn_012. The cycle is also very long (10 steps), reducing overall yield dramatically. The autocatalytic claim requires that valine (or pyruvate) from the cycle accelerates its own production, which is plausible for the transamination loop but not clearly demonstrated.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine: (1) the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic photochemistry pathway building valinonitrile from glyceraldehyde via acetone and isobutyraldehyde intermediates; (2) the classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993); (3) reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on Ni catalysts (Kaur et al., 2024); and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge (Johnson et al., 2009). The network begins with CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents, builds C2-C3 intermediates via formose chemistry on the surface, generates the critical branched C4 skeleton (acetone, isobutyraldehyde) through cyanosulfidic photochemistry, and converges on valine through multiple terminal reactions. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is generated via a speculative but chemically analogous reductive carboxylation of acetone on greigite (paralleling known pyruvate synthesis from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082). Key corrections from prior attempt: pyruvate decarboxylation correctly yields acetaldehyde (not acetone), acetone arises solely from photoreduction of dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al.), and Fischer-Tropsch synthesis is not invoked for branched products.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxidane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetone cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-3(2,5)4-6/h5H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanohydrin 26\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valinonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO\u2082 to formate (HCOO\u207b) via a two-electron transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. This is the first step of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog proposed for alkaline hydrothermal vents. Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces mimic ferredoxin-like electron transfer (Preiner et al., 2020; Herschy et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, strong reducing environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of formate (HCOO\u207b) on magnetite/FeS surfaces yields formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) by two-electron reduction. The reaction is thermodynamically uphill in dilute solution but favored by mineral surface adsorption, high H\u2082 fugacity, and continuous product removal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde is a critical C\u2081 building block. While its hydrothermal production from formate is low-yield, mineral surfaces stabilize intermediates. Magnetite and FeS have been shown to facilitate stepwise CO\u2082 reduction under hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020). Formaldehyde is also produced in atmospheric photochemistry and delivered by meteorites.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction initiation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH ~10-11, warm conditions with mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation in the presence of Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate minerals. The first formaldehyde is umpoled (through a Cannizzaro-type mechanism or mineral-assisted tautomerization to enolizable species) to act as a nucleophile, attacking a second formaldehyde molecule to form glycolaldehyde (C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is a well-known prebiotic route to sugars from formaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize sugar intermediates against degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite clay concentrates formaldehyde and catalyzes condensations. The reaction requires basic conditions and a C\u2082 'seed' or mineral catalysis for initiation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool with borate minerals to stabilize glyceraldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde acts as enolizable nucleophile; its enolate attacks formaldehyde to yield glyceraldehyde (C\u2083H\u2086O\u2083). Borate complexation of the diol stabilizes the product against retro-aldol or Cannizzaro degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde is a key formose reaction step. Borate complexation is critical for stabilizing glyceraldehyde, as demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). This provides the essential C\u2083 sugar precursor for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Isomerization of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild aqueous conditions; keto-enol tautomerism on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein transformation) to form dihydroxyacetone via the common enediol intermediate. Clay surfaces facilitate this isomerization by adsorbing and orienting the substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The glyceraldehyde \u21cc dihydroxyacetone equilibrium is well-known in sugar chemistry. In the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic scheme, glyceraldehyde partially converts to dihydroxyacetone, which is then photoreduced to acetone. This isomerization occurs readily in aqueous solution at neutral to basic pH.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreductive deoxygenation of dihydroxyacetone to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu\u2082S (cuprous sulfide)\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~254 nm), H\u2082S as terminal reductant, phosphate buffer, sunlit shallow pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light excites Cu(I) to Cu(I)* which reduces dihydroxyacetone via sequential 1-electron transfers, removing hydroxyl groups as water. H\u2082S serves as the sacrificial reductant, regenerating Cu(I) from Cu(II) and producing elemental sulfur. The two hydroxyl groups are reductively removed to yield acetone (propan-2-one).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde/dihydroxyacetone is photoreduced to acetone under UV irradiation in the presence of H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Cu\u2082S minerals can supply Cu(I) and generate HS\u207b from cyanide. This is the key step that generates the branched carbon skeleton precursor for valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN \u2192 acetone cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (base-catalyzed)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Dark reaction (no UV needed), mildly basic pH, aqueous pool with dissolved HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone in a nucleophilic addition. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield acetone cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile). This is a reversible reaction favored by moderate HCN concentrations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) showed that acetone reacts with HCN to form acetone cyanohydrin (compound 23 in their scheme) as the first step of the C\u2083\u2192C\u2084 homologation. This is a classic cyanohydrin formation, well-precedented in organic chemistry and plausible under prebiotic conditions where HCN is concentrated in evaporitic pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoreduction cascade: acetone cyanohydrin to isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu\u2082S (cuprous sulfide)\", \"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling on sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (~254 nm), H\u2082S reductant, multi-step: (1) dark H\u2082S addition gives \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24, (2) UV photoreduction gives thioamide 25, (3) further reduction/hydrolysis gives isobutyraldehyde. Sequential light/dark cycles.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1 (dark): H\u2082S adds to the nitrile of acetone cyanohydrin, converting CN to thioamide (C=S) and yielding \u03b1-hydroxythioamide (compound 24). Step 2 (UV): Photoreduction with H\u2082S removes the \u03b1-hydroxyl group, yielding thioamide 25. Step 3 (UV/hydrolysis): The thioamide is photolyzed/hydrolyzed to release the aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylpropanal) with loss of the sulfur moiety. Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on sulfide minerals mediates the electron transfers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This multi-step cascade is central to Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem., Fig. 1b). The conversion of acetone cyanohydrin through thioamide intermediates (compounds 24, 25) to the branched aldehyde isobutyraldehyde is the key chain-homologation step. Yields of individual steps were 40-70% (Table 1 in Patel et al.). This reaction series solves the major open problem of generating the branched C\u2084 carbon skeleton needed for valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: isobutyraldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin 26\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (mildly basic conditions)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Dark reaction, aqueous solution, HCN traps the aldehyde product from rxn_008\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde in a nucleophilic 1,2-addition. Protonation of the alkoxide gives 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (cyanohydrin 26, compound 26 in Patel et al.).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) showed that HCN present in the reaction mixture traps isobutyraldehyde as cyanohydrin 26 during the photoreduction cascade. This prevents loss of the volatile aldehyde and channels the carbon skeleton toward the aminonitrile. The reaction is spontaneous under the conditions used.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonolysis of cyanohydrin 26 to valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (NH\u2083 acts as nucleophilic amine source)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH ~9-10, excess NH\u2083, room temperature aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-hydroxyl group of cyanohydrin 26 is displaced by NH\u2083 via an SN2-like mechanism (or via elimination to an \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated nitrile followed by conjugate addition of NH\u2083). The product is 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valinonitrile, compound 27).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) reported that NH\u2083 addition to cyanohydrin 26 gave valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27) in ~42% yield (Table 1). This is the penultimate step to valine in the cyanosulfidic pathway. The high pH needed for free NH\u2083 is consistent with evaporitic pools near volcanic sources.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay, Zn\u00b2\u207a or other divalent cations\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10 (free NH\u2083 required, pKaH \u2248 9.2), evaporitic pool with concentrated reactants. DAP (diamidophosphate) can enable reaction at neutral pH.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: Isobutyraldehyde condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base), with loss of H\u2082O. Step 2: Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) adds to the electrophilic carbon of the imine in a nucleophilic 1,2-addition, yielding valinonitrile (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile). Divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Mg\u00b2\u207a) stabilize the imine intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Miller & Schlesinger (1993) identified isobutyraldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor to valine.' The Strecker synthesis is the classical prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids via aminonitrile intermediates. Powner et al. (2019, Commun. Chem.) showed that DAP promotes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH with 73-quantitative% yields of N-phosphoroaminonitriles from aldehydes. Metal salts (Mg\u00b2\u207a, Ca\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) catalyze imine formation (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of valinonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"acid or base catalysis, or thermal\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Warm acidic or basic aqueous solution; wet-dry cycling can drive hydrolysis. Two-step: nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of valinonitrile undergoes sequential hydrolysis: (1) nucleophilic addition of H\u2082O to C\u2261N gives an amide intermediate (valinamide), then (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid) + NH\u2083. Acid catalysis protonates the nitrile nitrogen, activating it toward water attack.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the terminal step of all Strecker-type and cyanosulfidic pathways. This reaction is well-precedented in prebiotic chemistry and proceeds under mildly acidic or basic conditions with gentle heating. In Miller-type experiments, aminonitriles hydrolyze to amino acids over days to weeks at room temperature (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar H\u2082/CO\u2082)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, high H\u2082 fugacity. Acetone transported from surface environment into vent system.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetone adsorbs onto the Fe\u2083S\u2084 mineral surface. CO\u2082 is reductively activated and inserted at the C1 position adjacent to the carbonyl, forming a C-C bond. Concurrent reduction by H\u2082 (dissociated on the mineral surface) yields 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). This is analogous to the established greigite-catalyzed reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"SPECULATIVE but chemically analogous to demonstrated reactions. Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 fixation produces pyruvate from C\u2082 precursors (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2017). By direct analogy, reductive carboxylation of acetone (C\u2083 ketone) to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (C\u2085 \u03b1-keto acid) follows the same mechanism with a branched substrate. The literature (Kaur et al., 2024) identifies the prebiotic source of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate as an open question; this represents one plausible abiotic route. No direct experimental demonstration exists for this specific reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on Ni catalyst\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H\u2082\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni nanoparticles (or Ni-Fe meteoritic material)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-8, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, 72h reaction time. Cool hydrothermal vent mixing zone or meteorite-bearing pool.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) at the C2 keto position. The imine is then hydrogenated by H\u2082 on the Ni catalyst surface, reducing C=N to C-NH\u2082 and yielding L/D-valine. The Ni surface dissociates H\u2082 and transfers hydrides to the adsorbed substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) directly demonstrated this reaction: Ni nanoparticles (10 mol% Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083) and ground Aletai meteorite powder (18 mol% Ni) catalyzed H\u2082-driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 5 bar H\u2082. Yields of amino + hydroxy acids were 6-84% depending on catalyst, with ~50% for Ni. Pd gave >80% yield with >5:1 amino:hydroxy acid selectivity. Natural analogs include pentlandite and Ni-bearing FeS in alkaline hydrothermal vents.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge producing valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"800-1200K (spark), 290-310K (aqueous trap)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge (lightning analog)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing atmosphere (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O vapor), spark electrodes, aqueous collection flask. Valine is a trace product among ~40 amino acids.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge dissociates CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and H\u2082O into radicals (CH\u2083\u00b7, NH\u2082\u00b7, OH\u00b7, H\u00b7, CN\u00b7). Radical recombination and rearrangement in the cooling gas produce HCN, aldehydes (including isobutyraldehyde), and NH\u2083, which then undergo Strecker chemistry in the aqueous phase. Branched aldehydes form via radical recombination of CH\u2083\u00b7 with CH\u2083CH\u00b7 giving (CH\u2083)\u2082CH\u00b7, which reacts with CO or HCO to yield isobutyraldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed Stanley Miller's original 1953 spark-discharge samples and detected valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids. The mechanism involves atmospheric radical chemistry feeding aqueous Strecker reactions. Valine is a minor product (trace ppm), but its presence confirms branched amino acids form abiotically. The reducing atmosphere (CH\u2084 + NH\u2083) is essential; neutral atmospheres give much lower yields.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO\u2082 reduction on Fe\u2083S\u2084/Fe\u2083O\u2084 surfaces: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde (via C-C coupling) \u2192 pyruvate (via oxidative carboxylation of acetaldehyde with CO\u2082). The mineral surface provides reducing electrons from H\u2082 oxidation and catalytic sites for C-C bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on greigite/magnetite surfaces is established in origin-of-life chemistry (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2017; Preiner et al., 2020). Pyruvate is the central hub of proto-metabolism and feeds into multiple downstream pathways including alanine synthesis and the branched-chain keto acid network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface (or thermal)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild hydrothermal conditions; decarboxylation is facile at >80\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, releasing CO\u2082 and yielding acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). This is a well-known reaction that proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The pyrite surface may lower the activation barrier by coordinating the carboxylate group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 is well-established in chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures (>80\u00b0C). CRITICAL CORRECTION from prior attempt: pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO), NOT acetone (CH\u2083COCH\u2083). Acetone requires a different precursor (dihydroxyacetone photoreduction, as in rxn_006). This reaction is important for connecting hydrothermal pyruvate to surface C\u2082 chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Ni/Fe minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"290-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H\u2082\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-8, NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, cool vent mixing zone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate condenses with NH\u2083 to form pyruvate imine; this is hydrogenated on the Ni catalyst surface by H\u2082 to yield alanine. Analogous to rxn_014 but with the simpler C\u2083 substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated reductive amination of multiple \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate on Ni catalysts with H\u2082 and NH\u2083. Alanine is a major product of this reaction and is needed as an amino group donor for the transamination route to valine (rxn_019). This connects hydrothermal H\u2082 chemistry to amino acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a or other divalent metal ions (prebiotic transaminase analogs)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, concentrated prebiotic pool with both substrates. Metal ions or pyridoxal-like cofactors (e.g., pyridoxal from photochemical synthesis) catalyze the amino group transfer.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine's amino group is transferred to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via a Schiff base intermediate. The amino acid first forms an aldimine with a metal-bound carbonyl cofactor (or directly with the keto acid in the presence of metal ions). Tautomerization of the aldimine to a ketimine, followed by hydrolysis, transfers the amino group from alanine to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination is a fundamental biochemical reaction and has prebiotic analogs. Metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) can catalyze transamination in the absence of enzymes (Snell, 1945; Metzler & Snell, 1952). This reaction connects the Kaur et al. reductive amination network to biological amino acid metabolism. The regeneration of pyruvate makes this a proto-catalytic cycle.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full Patel cyanosulfidic pathway via ammonolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete route from CO\u2082 through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then cyanosulfidic photoreduction to acetone and isobutyraldehyde, cyanohydrin trapping with HCN, ammonolysis with NH\u2083 to valinonitrile, and hydrolysis to valine. This is the primary Patel et al. (2015) route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde + Strecker synthesis hybrid\",\n      \"description\": \"Follows the Patel et al. route through isobutyraldehyde generation, but then uses classical Strecker condensation (isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile) rather than the stepwise cyanohydrin/ammonolysis route. Converges at valinonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 hydrothermal reductive carboxylation \u2192 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry generates acetone from glyceraldehyde. Acetone is then reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite in a hydrothermal setting (speculative, analogous to pyruvate synthesis). Finally, Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024) converts \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 transamination with alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetone generated via cyanosulfidic photoreduction is reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (hydrothermal). Alanine (from hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate) then donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via metal-catalyzed transamination, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge direct route\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical Miller-Urey synthesis from reducing atmosphere gases (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O). Electrical discharge produces radicals that recombine into HCN and aldehydes (including branched isobutyraldehyde), which undergo Strecker reactions in the aqueous phase to yield valine as a trace product among ~40 amino acids.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 alanine + transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate synthesized hydrothermally from CO\u2082 is reductively aminated to alanine using Ni/Fe catalysts and H\u2082. Separately, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (from reductive carboxylation of acetone) serves as the amino group acceptor. Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine yields valine and regenerates pyruvate, forming a proto-catalytic cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Short Strecker route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Assumes isobutyraldehyde is available (from cyanosulfidic photoreduction or other sources). Direct Strecker condensation with NH\u2083 and HCN gives valinonitrile, which hydrolyzes to valine. This is the most parsimonious route once the branched aldehyde exists.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Short Patel ammonolysis route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"From isobutyraldehyde, HCN trapping gives cyanohydrin 26, followed by NH\u2083 addition to give valinonitrile 27, then hydrolysis to valine. This is the terminal portion of the Patel et al. pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination from pre-formed \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Assumes \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available (from reductive carboxylation or other prebiotic sources). Direct H\u2082-driven reductive amination on Ni catalysts converts it to valine. This is the Kaur et al. (2024) route in its simplest form.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent Hydrothermal-Surface pathway via acetone hub\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates environmental interconnection: CO\u2082 is fixed hydrothermally (rxn_001, rxn_002), formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose and cyanosulfidic chemistry build glyceraldehyde and acetone (rxn_003-006). Acetone then feeds BOTH the cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde route (Surface, rxn_007-008 \u2192 rxn_011 \u2192 rxn_012) AND the reductive carboxylation route (Hydrothermal, rxn_013 \u2192 rxn_014). Two independent terminal pathways converge from the same hub molecule.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetone is the critical branched C\u2083 hub, formed exclusively by photoreduction of dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al. 2015). It feeds into TWO divergent routes: (1) the cyanosulfidic photoreduction cascade to isobutyraldehyde, and (2) the speculative hydrothermal reductive carboxylation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde is the key branched C\u2084 aldehyde, generated from the cyanosulfidic thioamide cascade (Patel et al. 2015). It feeds into TWO convergent routes to valinonitrile: (1) the Patel et al. cyanohydrin + ammonolysis pathway, and (2) the classical Strecker synthesis (Miller & Schlesinger 1993).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27) is the penultimate precursor to valine, receiving input from TWO independent pathways: (1) Patel et al. ammonolysis of cyanohydrin 26, and (2) classical Strecker condensation. Both converge on hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine (target) is the terminal convergence point, formed via FOUR distinct routes: (1) valinonitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012), (2) Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_014), (3) Miller-Urey spark discharge (rxn_015), and (4) transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine (rxn_019).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub: synthesized hydrothermally from CO\u2082 (rxn_016) and regenerated by transamination (rxn_019). It feeds into alanine synthesis (rxn_018) and thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde (rxn_017), connecting hydrothermal and surface chemistry.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine: (1) the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic photochemistry pathway building valinonitrile from glyceraldehyde via acetone and isobutyraldehyde intermediates; (2) the classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993); (3) reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on Ni catalysts (Kaur et al., 2024); and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge (Johnson et al., 2009). The network begins with CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents, builds C2-C3 intermediates via formose chemistry on the surface, generates the critical branched C4 skeleton (acetone, isobutyraldehyde) through cyanosulfidic photochemistry, and converges on valine through multiple terminal reactions. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is generated via a speculative but chemically analogous reductive carboxylation of acetone on greigite (paralleling known pyruvate synthesis from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082). Key corrections from prior attempt: pyruvate decarboxylation correctly yields acetaldehyde (not acetone), acetone arises solely from photoreduction of dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al.), and Fischer-Tropsch synthesis is not invoked for branched products.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O", "iupac_name": "propan-2-one", "common_name": "acetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetone cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-3(2,5)4-6/h5H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "cyanohydrin 26", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valinonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface, which acts as an analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO\u2082 to formate (HCOO\u207b) via a two-electron transfer.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. This is the first step of the acetyl-CoA pathway analog proposed for alkaline hydrothermal vents. Fe\u2083S\u2084 surfaces mimic ferredoxin-like electron transfer (Preiner et al., 2020; Herschy et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, strong reducing environment"}, "mechanism": "Further reduction of formate (HCOO\u207b) on magnetite/FeS surfaces yields formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) by two-electron reduction. The reaction is thermodynamically uphill in dilute solution but favored by mineral surface adsorption, high H\u2082 fugacity, and continuous product removal.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde is a critical C\u2081 building block. While its hydrothermal production from formate is low-yield, mineral surfaces stabilize intermediates. Magnetite and FeS have been shown to facilitate stepwise CO\u2082 reduction under hydrothermal conditions (Preiner et al., 2020). Formaldehyde is also produced in atmospheric photochemistry and delivered by meteorites."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose reaction initiation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH ~10-11, warm conditions with mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation in the presence of Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate minerals. The first formaldehyde is umpoled (through a Cannizzaro-type mechanism or mineral-assisted tautomerization to enolizable species) to act as a nucleophile, attacking a second formaldehyde molecule to form glycolaldehyde (C\u2082H\u2084O\u2082).", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is a well-known prebiotic route to sugars from formaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize sugar intermediates against degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Montmorillonite clay concentrates formaldehyde and catalyzes condensations. The reaction requires basic conditions and a C\u2082 'seed' or mineral catalysis for initiation."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool with borate minerals to stabilize glyceraldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde acts as enolizable nucleophile; its enolate attacks formaldehyde to yield glyceraldehyde (C\u2083H\u2086O\u2083). Borate complexation of the diol stabilizes the product against retro-aldol or Cannizzaro degradation.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde is a key formose reaction step. Borate complexation is critical for stabilizing glyceraldehyde, as demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). This provides the essential C\u2083 sugar precursor for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Isomerization of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild aqueous conditions; keto-enol tautomerism on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein transformation) to form dihydroxyacetone via the common enediol intermediate. Clay surfaces facilitate this isomerization by adsorbing and orienting the substrate.", "reasoning": "The glyceraldehyde \u21cc dihydroxyacetone equilibrium is well-known in sugar chemistry. In the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic scheme, glyceraldehyde partially converts to dihydroxyacetone, which is then photoreduced to acetone. This isomerization occurs readily in aqueous solution at neutral to basic pH."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Photoreductive deoxygenation of dihydroxyacetone to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu\u2082S (cuprous sulfide)", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (~254 nm), H\u2082S as terminal reductant, phosphate buffer, sunlit shallow pool"}, "mechanism": "UV light excites Cu(I) to Cu(I)* which reduces dihydroxyacetone via sequential 1-electron transfers, removing hydroxyl groups as water. H\u2082S serves as the sacrificial reductant, regenerating Cu(I) from Cu(II) and producing elemental sulfur. The two hydroxyl groups are reductively removed to yield acetone (propan-2-one).", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde/dihydroxyacetone is photoreduced to acetone under UV irradiation in the presence of H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Cu\u2082S minerals can supply Cu(I) and generate HS\u207b from cyanide. This is the key step that generates the branched carbon skeleton precursor for valine."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN \u2192 acetone cyanohydrin", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (base-catalyzed)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Dark reaction (no UV needed), mildly basic pH, aqueous pool with dissolved HCN"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone in a nucleophilic addition. The resulting alkoxide is protonated to yield acetone cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile). This is a reversible reaction favored by moderate HCN concentrations.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) showed that acetone reacts with HCN to form acetone cyanohydrin (compound 23 in their scheme) as the first step of the C\u2083\u2192C\u2084 homologation. This is a classic cyanohydrin formation, well-precedented in organic chemistry and plausible under prebiotic conditions where HCN is concentrated in evaporitic pools."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoreduction cascade: acetone cyanohydrin to isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu\u2082S (cuprous sulfide)", "stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling on sulfide minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (~254 nm), H\u2082S reductant, multi-step: (1) dark H\u2082S addition gives \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24, (2) UV photoreduction gives thioamide 25, (3) further reduction/hydrolysis gives isobutyraldehyde. Sequential light/dark cycles."}, "mechanism": "Step 1 (dark): H\u2082S adds to the nitrile of acetone cyanohydrin, converting CN to thioamide (C=S) and yielding \u03b1-hydroxythioamide (compound 24). Step 2 (UV): Photoreduction with H\u2082S removes the \u03b1-hydroxyl group, yielding thioamide 25. Step 3 (UV/hydrolysis): The thioamide is photolyzed/hydrolyzed to release the aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylpropanal) with loss of the sulfur moiety. Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on sulfide minerals mediates the electron transfers.", "reasoning": "This multi-step cascade is central to Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem., Fig. 1b). The conversion of acetone cyanohydrin through thioamide intermediates (compounds 24, 25) to the branched aldehyde isobutyraldehyde is the key chain-homologation step. Yields of individual steps were 40-70% (Table 1 in Patel et al.). This reaction series solves the major open problem of generating the branched C\u2084 carbon skeleton needed for valine."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: isobutyraldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin 26", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (mildly basic conditions)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Dark reaction, aqueous solution, HCN traps the aldehyde product from rxn_008"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde in a nucleophilic 1,2-addition. Protonation of the alkoxide gives 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (cyanohydrin 26, compound 26 in Patel et al.).", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) showed that HCN present in the reaction mixture traps isobutyraldehyde as cyanohydrin 26 during the photoreduction cascade. This prevents loss of the volatile aldehyde and channels the carbon skeleton toward the aminonitrile. The reaction is spontaneous under the conditions used."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Ammonolysis of cyanohydrin 26 to valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27)", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (NH\u2083 acts as nucleophilic amine source)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH ~9-10, excess NH\u2083, room temperature aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-hydroxyl group of cyanohydrin 26 is displaced by NH\u2083 via an SN2-like mechanism (or via elimination to an \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated nitrile followed by conjugate addition of NH\u2083). The product is 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (valinonitrile, compound 27).", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) reported that NH\u2083 addition to cyanohydrin 26 gave valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27) in ~42% yield (Table 1). This is the penultimate step to valine in the cyanosulfidic pathway. The high pH needed for free NH\u2083 is consistent with evaporitic pools near volcanic sources."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay, Zn\u00b2\u207a or other divalent cations", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8-10 (free NH\u2083 required, pKaH \u2248 9.2), evaporitic pool with concentrated reactants. DAP (diamidophosphate) can enable reaction at neutral pH."}, "mechanism": "Step 1: Isobutyraldehyde condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base), with loss of H\u2082O. Step 2: Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) adds to the electrophilic carbon of the imine in a nucleophilic 1,2-addition, yielding valinonitrile (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile). Divalent metal ions (Zn\u00b2\u207a, Mg\u00b2\u207a) stabilize the imine intermediate.", "reasoning": "Miller & Schlesinger (1993) identified isobutyraldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor to valine.' The Strecker synthesis is the classical prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids via aminonitrile intermediates. Powner et al. (2019, Commun. Chem.) showed that DAP promotes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH with 73-quantitative% yields of N-phosphoroaminonitriles from aldehydes. Metal salts (Mg\u00b2\u207a, Ca\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a, Zn\u00b2\u207a) catalyze imine formation (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Hydrolysis of valinonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "acid or base catalysis, or thermal", "aqueous": true, "other": "Warm acidic or basic aqueous solution; wet-dry cycling can drive hydrolysis. Two-step: nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid."}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of valinonitrile undergoes sequential hydrolysis: (1) nucleophilic addition of H\u2082O to C\u2261N gives an amide intermediate (valinamide), then (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid) + NH\u2083. Acid catalysis protonates the nitrile nitrogen, activating it toward water attack.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the terminal step of all Strecker-type and cyanosulfidic pathways. This reaction is well-precedented in prebiotic chemistry and proceeds under mildly acidic or basic conditions with gentle heating. In Miller-type experiments, aminonitriles hydrolyze to amino acids over days to weeks at room temperature (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar H\u2082/CO\u2082)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, high H\u2082 fugacity. Acetone transported from surface environment into vent system."}, "mechanism": "Acetone adsorbs onto the Fe\u2083S\u2084 mineral surface. CO\u2082 is reductively activated and inserted at the C1 position adjacent to the carbonyl, forming a C-C bond. Concurrent reduction by H\u2082 (dissociated on the mineral surface) yields 3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate). This is analogous to the established greigite-catalyzed reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate.", "reasoning": "SPECULATIVE but chemically analogous to demonstrated reactions. Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 fixation produces pyruvate from C\u2082 precursors (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2017). By direct analogy, reductive carboxylation of acetone (C\u2083 ketone) to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (C\u2085 \u03b1-keto acid) follows the same mechanism with a branched substrate. The literature (Kaur et al., 2024) identifies the prebiotic source of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate as an open question; this represents one plausible abiotic route. No direct experimental demonstration exists for this specific reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on Ni catalyst", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-310K", "pressure": "5 bar H\u2082", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles (or Ni-Fe meteoritic material)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-8, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, 72h reaction time. Cool hydrothermal vent mixing zone or meteorite-bearing pool."}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate condenses with NH\u2083 to form an imine (Schiff base) at the C2 keto position. The imine is then hydrogenated by H\u2082 on the Ni catalyst surface, reducing C=N to C-NH\u2082 and yielding L/D-valine. The Ni surface dissociates H\u2082 and transfers hydrides to the adsorbed substrate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) directly demonstrated this reaction: Ni nanoparticles (10 mol% Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083) and ground Aletai meteorite powder (18 mol% Ni) catalyzed H\u2082-driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 5 bar H\u2082. Yields of amino + hydroxy acids were 6-84% depending on catalyst, with ~50% for Ni. Pd gave >80% yield with >5:1 amino:hydroxy acid selectivity. Natural analogs include pentlandite and Ni-bearing FeS in alkaline hydrothermal vents."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Miller-Urey spark discharge producing valine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "800-1200K (spark), 290-310K (aqueous trap)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electrical discharge (lightning analog)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing atmosphere (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O vapor), spark electrodes, aqueous collection flask. Valine is a trace product among ~40 amino acids."}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge dissociates CH\u2084, NH\u2083, and H\u2082O into radicals (CH\u2083\u00b7, NH\u2082\u00b7, OH\u00b7, H\u00b7, CN\u00b7). Radical recombination and rearrangement in the cooling gas produce HCN, aldehydes (including isobutyraldehyde), and NH\u2083, which then undergo Strecker chemistry in the aqueous phase. Branched aldehydes form via radical recombination of CH\u2083\u00b7 with CH\u2083CH\u00b7 giving (CH\u2083)\u2082CH\u00b7, which reacts with CO or HCO to yield isobutyraldehyde.", "reasoning": "Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed Stanley Miller's original 1953 spark-discharge samples and detected valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids. The mechanism involves atmospheric radical chemistry feeding aqueous Strecker reactions. Valine is a minor product (trace ppm), but its presence confirms branched amino acids form abiotically. The reducing atmosphere (CH\u2084 + NH\u2083) is essential; neutral atmospheres give much lower yields."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite, magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven fluid"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO\u2082 reduction on Fe\u2083S\u2084/Fe\u2083O\u2084 surfaces: CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde (via C-C coupling) \u2192 pyruvate (via oxidative carboxylation of acetaldehyde with CO\u2082). The mineral surface provides reducing electrons from H\u2082 oxidation and catalytic sites for C-C bond formation.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO\u2082 and H\u2082 on greigite/magnetite surfaces is established in origin-of-life chemistry (Roldan et al., 2015; Muchowska et al., 2017; Preiner et al., 2020). Pyruvate is the central hub of proto-metabolism and feeds into multiple downstream pathways including alanine synthesis and the branched-chain keto acid network."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface (or thermal)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild hydrothermal conditions; decarboxylation is facile at >80\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOOH) undergoes thermal decarboxylation at the \u03b1-keto position, releasing CO\u2082 and yielding acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). This is a well-known reaction that proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The pyrite surface may lower the activation barrier by coordinating the carboxylate group.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 is well-established in chemistry and occurs readily at hydrothermal temperatures (>80\u00b0C). CRITICAL CORRECTION from prior attempt: pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO), NOT acetone (CH\u2083COCH\u2083). Acetone requires a different precursor (dihydroxyacetone photoreduction, as in rxn_006). This reaction is important for connecting hydrothermal pyruvate to surface C\u2082 chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Ni/Fe minerals", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "290-350K", "pressure": "5 bar H\u2082", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-8, NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, cool vent mixing zone"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate condenses with NH\u2083 to form pyruvate imine; this is hydrogenated on the Ni catalyst surface by H\u2082 to yield alanine. Analogous to rxn_014 but with the simpler C\u2083 substrate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated reductive amination of multiple \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate on Ni catalysts with H\u2082 and NH\u2083. Alanine is a major product of this reaction and is needed as an amino group donor for the transamination route to valine (rxn_019). This connects hydrothermal H\u2082 chemistry to amino acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_020"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a or other divalent metal ions (prebiotic transaminase analogs)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, concentrated prebiotic pool with both substrates. Metal ions or pyridoxal-like cofactors (e.g., pyridoxal from photochemical synthesis) catalyze the amino group transfer."}, "mechanism": "Alanine's amino group is transferred to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via a Schiff base intermediate. The amino acid first forms an aldimine with a metal-bound carbonyl cofactor (or directly with the keto acid in the presence of metal ions). Tautomerization of the aldimine to a ketimine, followed by hydrolysis, transfers the amino group from alanine to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Transamination is a fundamental biochemical reaction and has prebiotic analogs. Metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a) can catalyze transamination in the absence of enzymes (Snell, 1945; Metzler & Snell, 1952). This reaction connects the Kaur et al. reductive amination network to biological amino acid metabolism. The regeneration of pyruvate makes this a proto-catalytic cycle."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full Patel cyanosulfidic pathway via ammonolysis", "description": "Complete route from CO\u2082 through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then cyanosulfidic photoreduction to acetone and isobutyraldehyde, cyanohydrin trapping with HCN, ammonolysis with NH\u2083 to valinonitrile, and hydrolysis to valine. This is the primary Patel et al. (2015) route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde + Strecker synthesis hybrid", "description": "Follows the Patel et al. route through isobutyraldehyde generation, but then uses classical Strecker condensation (isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile) rather than the stepwise cyanohydrin/ammonolysis route. Converges at valinonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 hydrothermal reductive carboxylation \u2192 reductive amination", "description": "Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry generates acetone from glyceraldehyde. Acetone is then reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite in a hydrothermal setting (speculative, analogous to pyruvate synthesis). Finally, Ni-catalyzed reductive amination (Kaur et al. 2024) converts \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 transamination with alanine", "description": "Acetone generated via cyanosulfidic photoreduction is reductively carboxylated to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (hydrothermal). Alanine (from hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate) then donates its amino group to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via metal-catalyzed transamination, yielding valine and regenerating pyruvate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_013", "rxn_016", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_018", "mol_020", "mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Miller-Urey spark discharge direct route", "description": "Classical Miller-Urey synthesis from reducing atmosphere gases (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O). Electrical discharge produces radicals that recombine into HCN and aldehydes (including branched isobutyraldehyde), which undergo Strecker reactions in the aqueous phase to yield valine as a trace product among ~40 amino acids.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": []}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 alanine + transamination route", "description": "Pyruvate synthesized hydrothermally from CO\u2082 is reductively aminated to alanine using Ni/Fe catalysts and H\u2082. Separately, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (from reductive carboxylation of acetone) serves as the amino group acceptor. Transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine yields valine and regenerates pyruvate, forming a proto-catalytic cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_016", "rxn_018", "rxn_013", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_020", "mol_022", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Short Strecker route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde", "description": "Assumes isobutyraldehyde is available (from cyanosulfidic photoreduction or other sources). Direct Strecker condensation with NH\u2083 and HCN gives valinonitrile, which hydrolyzes to valine. This is the most parsimonious route once the branched aldehyde exists.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Short Patel ammonolysis route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde", "description": "From isobutyraldehyde, HCN trapping gives cyanohydrin 26, followed by NH\u2083 addition to give valinonitrile 27, then hydrolysis to valine. This is the terminal portion of the Patel et al. pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Reductive amination from pre-formed \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "description": "Assumes \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available (from reductive carboxylation or other prebiotic sources). Direct H\u2082-driven reductive amination on Ni catalysts converts it to valine. This is the Kaur et al. (2024) route in its simplest form.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent Hydrothermal-Surface pathway via acetone hub", "description": "Demonstrates environmental interconnection: CO\u2082 is fixed hydrothermally (rxn_001, rxn_002), formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose and cyanosulfidic chemistry build glyceraldehyde and acetone (rxn_003-006). Acetone then feeds BOTH the cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde route (Surface, rxn_007-008 \u2192 rxn_011 \u2192 rxn_012) AND the reductive carboxylation route (Hydrothermal, rxn_013 \u2192 rxn_014). Two independent terminal pathways converge from the same hub molecule.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_018"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_017"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Acetone is the critical branched C\u2083 hub, formed exclusively by photoreduction of dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al. 2015). It feeds into TWO divergent routes: (1) the cyanosulfidic photoreduction cascade to isobutyraldehyde, and (2) the speculative hydrothermal reductive carboxylation to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde is the key branched C\u2084 aldehyde, generated from the cyanosulfidic thioamide cascade (Patel et al. 2015). It feeds into TWO convergent routes to valinonitrile: (1) the Patel et al. cyanohydrin + ammonolysis pathway, and (2) the classical Strecker synthesis (Miller & Schlesinger 1993).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_017", "description": "Valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27) is the penultimate precursor to valine, receiving input from TWO independent pathways: (1) Patel et al. ammonolysis of cyanohydrin 26, and (2) classical Strecker condensation. Both converge on hydrolysis to valine.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_019", "description": "Valine (target) is the terminal convergence point, formed via FOUR distinct routes: (1) valinonitrile hydrolysis (rxn_012), (2) Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_014), (3) Miller-Urey spark discharge (rxn_015), and (4) transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine (rxn_019).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": []}, {"molecule_id": "mol_020", "description": "Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub: synthesized hydrothermally from CO\u2082 (rxn_016) and regenerated by transamination (rxn_019). It feeds into alanine synthesis (rxn_018) and thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde (rxn_017), connecting hydrothermal and surface chemistry.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_016", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_017", "rxn_018"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 494942.11292266846, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T03:22:48.855092", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Valine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine: (1) the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic photochemistry pathway building valinonitrile from glyceraldehyde via acetone and isobutyraldehyde intermediates; (2) the classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde (Miller & Schlesinger, 1993); (3) reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on Ni catalysts (Kaur et al., 2024); and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge (Johnson et al., 2009). The network begins with CO\u2082 fixation in hydrothermal vents, builds C2-C3 intermediates via formose chemistry on the surface, generates the critical branched C4 skeleton (acetone, isobutyraldehyde) through cyanosulfidic photochemistry, and converges on valine through multiple terminal reactions. \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is generated via a speculative but chemically analogous reductive carboxylation of acetone on greigite (paralleling known pyruvate synthesis from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082). Key corrections from prior attempt: pyruvate decarboxylation correctly yields acetaldehyde (not acetone), acetone arises solely from photoreduction of dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al.), and Fischer-Tropsch synthesis is not invoked for branched products.\n\nMOLECULES (22 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CH4 (methane) [starting]\n  - mol_008: HCOO- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H6O3 (dihydroxyacetone) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6O (acetone) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H7NO (acetone cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H8O (isobutyraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H9NO (cyanohydrin 26) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C5H10N2 (valinonitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_018: C5H8O3 (alpha-ketoisovalerate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C5H11NO2 (valine) [target]\n  - mol_020: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_021: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_022: C3H7NO2 (alanine) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (19 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_008 (CO\u2082 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_008, mol_002 -> mol_009, mol_006 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_009 -> mol_010 (Formose reaction initiation: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_010, mol_009 -> mol_011 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_011 -> mol_012 (Isomerization of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_012, mol_005 -> mol_013 (Photoreductive deoxygenation of dihydroxyacetone to acetone) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_013, mol_004 -> mol_014 (Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN \u2192 acetone cyanohydrin) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_014, mol_005 -> mol_015 (Cyanosulfidic photoreduction cascade: acetone cyanohydrin to isobutyraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_015, mol_004 -> mol_016 (Cyanohydrin formation: isobutyraldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin 26) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_016, mol_003 -> mol_017 (Ammonolysis of cyanohydrin 26 to valinonitrile (aminonitrile 27)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_015, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_017 (Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_017, mol_006 -> mol_019 (Hydrolysis of valinonitrile to valine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_013: mol_013, mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_018 (Reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_014: mol_018, mol_002, mol_003 -> mol_019 (Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine on Ni catalyst) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_015: mol_007, mol_003, mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_019 (Miller-Urey spark discharge producing valine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_020 (Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_017: mol_020 -> mol_021, mol_001 (Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_018: mol_020, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_022 (Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Ni/Fe minerals) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_019: mol_018, mol_022 -> mol_019, mol_020 (Transamination: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + alanine \u2192 valine + pyruvate) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full Patel cyanosulfidic pathway via ammonolysis (11 steps)\n  - P2: Cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde + Strecker synthesis hybrid (10 steps)\n  - P3: Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 hydrothermal reductive carboxylation \u2192 reductive amination (8 steps)\n  - P4: Cyanosulfidic acetone \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 transamination with alanine (10 steps)\n  - P5: Miller-Urey spark discharge direct route (1 steps)\n  - P6: Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 alanine + transamination route (4 steps)\n  - P7: Short Strecker route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde (2 steps)\n  - P8: Short Patel ammonolysis route from pre-formed isobutyraldehyde (3 steps)\n  - P9: Reductive amination from pre-formed \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (1 steps)\n  - P10: Convergent Hydrothermal-Surface pathway via acetone hub (12 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_004, mol_013, mol_015, mol_017\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis Routes to Valine\nSeveral pathways have been proposed for abiotic valine formation. Classical Miller\u2013Urey\u2013type spark\u2010discharge experiments with a reducing gas mixture (H\u2082, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082O) generate dozens of amino acids; reanalysis of Miller\u2019s original samples detected valine (and its diastereomer isovaline) among dozens of products[1]. In these electric\u2010discharge experiments, the atmosphere is heated to ~800\u20131200\u202f\u00b0C in brief sparks and cooled, giving rise to Strecker\u2010type chemistry (see below). Valine is only a minor product under such conditions (glycine/alanine dominate), but its presence shows branched amino acids can arise from simple feedstocks[1].\nThe canonical Strecker synthesis is another obvious route: an aldehyde or ketone reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN to give an \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to an amino acid. For valine this requires isobutyraldehyde (2\u2011methylpropanal, (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) as the carbonyl. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) noted that \u201cisobutyraldehyde is the Strecker precursor to valine\u201d, while \u03b1\u2011ketoisovaleric acid (the transamination product of valine) also participates in these networks[2]. In practice, Strecker routes likely require high pH (because NH\u2083 has pK_aH\u22489.2)[3] and concentrated cyanide. Recent work shows that diamidophosphate (DAP) can promote Strecker syntheses at neutral pH, giving \u201cN\u2011phosphoro\u2011aminonitriles\u201d in high yield (73\u2013quantitative) from simple aldehydes and HCN[3]. By analogy, DAP or related salts could enable valine formation from isobutyraldehyde under mild conditions. However, Strecker reactions select poorly among substrates: Miller & Schlesinger found pantoic acid (from isobutyraldehyde) forms along with glycine, alanine and GABA without selectivity[4]. In summary, Strecker chemistry from isobutyraldehyde\u2009+\u2009NH\u2083\u2009+\u2009HCN is a plausible route to valine via valinonitrile, but it hinges on prebiotic supply of isobutyraldehyde (see Precursors).\nA modern variant is the cyanosulfidic photochemistry first detailed by Patel et al. (2015). In this scheme, HCN is reductively homologated under UV irradiation in the presence of H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox catalysts to build up carbon skeletons. Starting from simpler sugars and cyanide, the chemistry yields \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile precursors of valine (and leucine) via multi\u2010step dark/photochemical cycles. For example, glyceraldehyde and its acetone byproduct are converted (via \u03b1-hydroxythioamides and thioamides) into the cyanohydrin intermediate 26; subsequent addition of NH\u2083 then gives the valine aminonitrile (27)[5][6]. In Patel et al.\u2019s experiments, this 4-step homologation (Fig. 1b) proceeded in ~42% yield of 27[7]. Crucially, this route requires UV irradiation and H\u2082S as reductant; copper sulfide minerals (e.g. cuprous sulfide) can supply Cu(I) and generate HS\u207b from cyanide[8][9]. Thus the cyanosulfidic pathway converges on valine via a Strecker\u2010like aminonitrile, but built up in situ from HCN, small sugars and sulfide.\nA third route is metal\u2010catalyzed reductive amination of keto acids. Kaur et al. (2024) showed that under mild (22\u202f\u00b0C, pH 8) conditions, H\u2082 gas can reduce \u03b1\u2011ketoacids in the presence of NH\u2083 and metal catalysts to yield amino acids[10]. In that work, Ni nanoparticles (and even Ni-bearing meteorite powder) catalyzed H\u2082\u2010driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (the \u03b1\u2011keto acid of valine) into valine[10]. The reactions used 5 bar H\u2082, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, pH 7\u20138 water and 72 h reaction time; with Ni catalysts the combined yield of amino+hydroxy acids was 6\u201384% (valine was one product)[10]. (A Pd catalyst gave higher yields but with >5:1 selectivity of amino acid over the competing \u03b1\u2011hydroxy acid[10].) This \u201cmetabolism\u2010like\u201d hydrogenation network suggests alkaline hydrothermal vent settings (rich in H\u2082 and Ni\u2010Fe minerals) could produce valine by reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.\nOther proposed routes are less studied. For example, generalized formose-type chemistry (polymerization of H\u2082CO) can produce various aldehydes and sugars, but it is not known to yield branched C\u2083 aldehydes efficiently. Similarly, Fischer\u2013Tropsch synthesis on metal sulfides tends to give linear acids (acetate, pyruvate, etc.) rather than branched amino acids. Miller\u2013Urey experiments with added sulfide or formamide have been suggested to improve yields of certain amino acids, but specific valine yields are rarely reported. In summary, the main validated pathways to prebiotic valine are: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde[2], (2) photochemical homologation of HCN[5], (3) H\u2082\u2010driven reductive amination of \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate[10], and (4) complex spark\u2010discharge mixtures[1].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors\nAll known routes rely on larger precursors that embody valine\u2019s branched C\u2083 skeleton. In Strecker chemistry the key intermediate is isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO), which condenses with NH\u2083 and HCN to give valine\u2019s aminonitrile (valinonitrile). Miller & Schlesinger explicitly identified isobutyraldehyde as \u201cthe Strecker precursor to valine\u201d[2]. Similarly, \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate (3\u2011methyl\u20112\u2011oxobutanoate) is the immediate precursor in reductive amination routes; it can arise by transamination of valine or by a prior homologation (e.g. as a product of a reductive aldol sequence). In the cyanosulfidic pathway, smaller precursors feed into acetone and acetone derivatives: glyceraldehyde (a C\u2083 sugar) dehydrates/decays partly to dihydroxyacetone (acetone-3, C\u2083) and acetone itself, which then is converted (via thioamide intermediates) to cyanohydrin 26. The \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (formed by NH\u2083 addition) is the penultimate precursor to valine[5]. In all cases the ultimate atom sources are simple C, N, H compounds: HCN, HCHO, NH\u2083, H\u2082, CO\u2082 etc. The key branch\u2011forming steps thus involve either homologation (adding \u2013CH\u2082\u2013 units via HCN chemistry) or decarboxylation of longer keto acids.\nOther precursors can play roles. For example, formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde may polymerize on mineral surfaces to give higher aldols, but branched products are not favored thermodynamically. In the cyanosulfidic route, acetone originates from initial photoredox reduction of dihydroxyacetone (which itself comes from photoredox of glyceraldehyde). Thus dihydroxyacetone (acetone-2) and acetone (acetone-3) are intermediates en route to the valine nitrile[5]. Hydroxylated thioamides (e.g. compounds 24,28 in Patel et al.) and nitriles (26,30) appear transiently in that scheme. Importantly, ammonia (NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a) is a branch precursor (necessary for the \u2013NH\u2082 group in valine) and cyanide (HCN/CN\u207b) provides the \u2013CN unit in aminonitriles; their availability dictates each route\u2019s feasibility. In short, isobutyraldehyde and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the largest building blocks needed, while HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082, formaldehyde, and small sugars are the ubiquitous feedstocks from which these can be assembled.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions\nStrecker Synthesis (Chemical Condensation): Isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valine aminonitrile \u2192 valine after hydrolysis. Mechanistically, the aldehyde first forms an imine with NH\u2083, then CN\u207b adds to give the aminonitrile, which on water\u2010catalyzed hydrolysis yields valine. Conditions reported are aqueous, often neutral\u2010to-basic pH (~8\u201310) because free NH\u2083 is needed[3]. Miller (1993) showed that adding metal salts (Mg\u00b2\u207a, Ca\u00b2\u207a, transition metals) catalyzes reactions of \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) under Strecker-like conditions[2]. Diamidophosphate (DAP) enables the \u201cStrecker\u201d at neutral pH by temporarily masking NH\u2083 and activating HCN/aldehyde[3]. Typical yields depend on concentration and pH; classical Strecker gives roughly 10\u201350% conversion to aminonitrile for favorable substrates, although yields for valine\u2019s nitrile specifically are not routinely reported. One experimental metric: Powner et al. achieved 73\u2013quantitative% yield of N-phosphoro-aminonitriles at pH 7 from simple aldehydes[3] (analogous conditions should work for isobutyraldehyde). After Strecker, heating or acid can hydrolyze the nitrile to the amino acid. The environment is typically a shallow pool or evaporating basin where HCN and NH\u2083 concentrate and ammonia is deprotonated (e.g. volcanic lakes or drying geothermal ponds).\nCyanosulfidic Photoredox (Patel et al. 2015): This multi-step mechanism uses UV light and sulfide. Key steps (Fig. 1b in [5]) are:\n\u2022\tAddition of HCN to ketones: Acetone (formed from glyceraldehyde/dihydroxyacetone) reacts with HCN to give cyanohydrin 23. This is typically reversible, but under the \u201cdark\u201d addition of HS\u207b it converts to an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide (compound 24)[11].\n\u2022\tPhotoreduction: UV light with H\u2082S reductant converts the hydroxylthioamide to a thioamide (25) and further to an aldehyde (byloss of S and H insertion). Continuing UV in H\u2082S + HCN traps the aldehyde as cyanohydrin 26[12].\n\u2022\tAmmonia addition: Finally, NH\u2083 adds to cyanohydrin 26 to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (valine precursor)[13].\nConditions were aqueous, UV irradiation (\u2248254 nm or broad UV), presence of H\u2082S (hydrosulfide), phosphate buffer, and catalytic Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on sulfide minerals. Patel et al. carried out these steps in sequence (often with intermediate purification) under room-temperature conditions. Table 1 in [5] shows that converting 26\u219227 gave 42% yield in one step. In practice, overall yields for each homologation step were on the order of tens of percent[5]. Side products include simpler amino acids (alanine, glycine) from parallel pathways, but valine\u2019s pathway was clearly observed. This chemistry is most plausible in sunlit terrestrial ponds with abundant HCN and HS\u207b (e.g. sulfidic lakes or streams after meteorite impacts[14]).\nReductive Amination (Hydrogenation): Kaur et al. demonstrated a straightforward mechanism: an \u03b1-keto acid is hydrogenated and aminated to give the amino acid. For valine, 2-oxoisovalerate + H\u2082 + NH\u2084\u207a \u2192 valine + H\u2082O. This is essentially the reverse of branched amino acid dehydrogenases. They used metallic catalysts (10 mol% Ni or Pd on support) or Ni-rich meteorite powder, 5 bar H\u2082 gas, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, at pH 8 and 22\u202f\u00b0C[15]. After 72 h, Ni catalysts yielded mixtures of valine and a mixture of hydroxy acids (from partial reduction of the ketoacid); overall conversion was 6\u201384% (depending on catalyst), typically ~50% with Ni[10]. Pd catalysts gave higher yields (~80%) and >5:1 selectivity for amino vs hydroxy acids. No reaction occurred without catalyst[10]. Thus, mild alkaline hydrothermal fluids (cool vents or mixing zones) rich in H\u2082 and NH\u2083 could produce valine from keto precursors with Ni/Fe minerals. Yields are high if the ketoacid is available, and the chemistry tolerates neutral to slightly alkaline pH and ambient to moderate temperature.\nSpark and Miller-type Experiments: In these, a gaseous mixture (e.g. 50% CH\u2084, 20% NH\u2083, 30% H\u2082O vapor) is discharged by spark. Products include amino acids, cyanides, and hydrocarbons. Early analyses found glycine, alanine, aspartic acid in mg yield per liter; valine was present at trace levels. Johnson et al. (2009) reported dozens of amino acids, including valine and isovaline, in Miller\u2019s 1953 samples[1]. Quantitative yields for valine weren\u2019t given, but glycine was tens of \u03bcg/mL in the total liquid. Such discharges represent surface/atmospheric conditions (lightning or volcanism).\nEach route has trade-offs in yield and selectivity. Strecker is efficient for many amino acids in one pot, but requires free NH\u2083 (or masked NH\u2083 like DAP) and yields mixtures (glycine, alanine often dominate). Cyanosulfidic chemistry is selective but complex, needing sequential addition of reagents and UV exposure[16]. Hydrogenation gives good selectivity but needs specific keto precursors. In all cases, yields of valine are modest (single-digit to tens of percent per step) and accompanied by by-products.\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces\nMineral surfaces are central to many proposed valine syntheses. Nickel and Iron Sulfides: Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user famously invoked NiS/FeS as \u201cproto-enzymes.\u201d In Kaur et al.\u2019s experiments, Ni dispersed on silica or FeNi meteorite powder was required[15]. Specifically, Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) and ground Aletai meteorite (18 mol% Ni) were used as H\u2082 hydrogenation catalysts[15]. Natural analogs include pentlandite [(Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088] or mackinawite (FeS) in hydrothermal vents, which can reduce CO\u2082 and nitriles. Copper Sulfides: Patel et al. note that Cu\u2082S or covellite could catalyze their photochemical cycles. Cu(I) forms (e.g. chalcopyrite) can facilitate HCN cross-coupling and photoredox; indeed, Cu(I)/Cu(II) on sulfides is a photosensitizer that drives the HCN homologation with H\u2082S[9]. Cu(II) minerals (malachite) might also transiently form, but CuS is key. Pyrite/Greigite: Iron sulfide (FeS\u2082, Fe\u2083S\u2084) surfaces have been shown to catalyze reduction of nitriles and CO\u2082. While specific studies on valine are lacking, FeS/FeS\u2082 could (by analogy to acetate/pyruvate synthesis) facilitate C\u2013N bond formation or HCN polymerization.\nMontmorillonite and Clays: Smectite clays like montmorillonite can concentrate organics and catalyze certain condensations (e.g. amino acid polymerization). They may help align isobutyraldehyde, HCN and NH\u2083 for Strecker synthesis in drying pools, although direct evidence for valine-specific catalysis is scarce. Experiments have shown clay surfaces strongly adsorb amino acids (including valine)[17], which could assist in concentrating them but can also inhibit reactivity.\nOther Minerals: Zn\u00b2\u207a and other divalent cations accelerate Strecker steps (by stabilizing imines)[2]. Transition\u2010metal phosphides (schreibersite, (Fe,Ni)\u2083P) can hydrolyze to yield phosphate and reduced phosphorus (P\u2083\u207b) which may activate feedstocks, though their role for valine is indirect. NiFe alloys (from meteorites) and iron oxides (magnetite, hematite) also feature in origin-of-life scenarios, but no specific valine synthesis has been demonstrated on them.\nIn summary, Ni/Fe sulfide minerals (present in vents and meteorites) and copper sulfides (in terrestrial Hadean environments) are the main catalysts identified for valine precursors[15][9]. Many origin-of-life studies emphasize these minerals for amino\u2010acid chemistry, so they likely played a role in any prebiotic valine formation.\nExperimental Evidence\n\u2022\tMiller\u2013Urey experiments: Stanley Miller\u2019s 1953 spark\u2011discharge (CH\u2084\u2013NH\u2083\u2013H\u2082O) produced amino acids. Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed original residues and found valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids[1]. This confirms branched amino acids can form abiotically. Glycine/alanine dominated quantitatively, so valine\u2019s yield was low (trace ppm in solution), but its presence is significant.\n\u2022\tStrecker experiments: Although classic Strecker syntheses were developed in the lab (mid-19th century), application to prebiotic chemistry was discussed by Or\u00f3 and others. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) showed that heating isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN (in formamide/water) yields pantoic acid, noting isobutyraldehyde\u2019s connection to valine[2]. They reported that metal salts (Mg, Ca, Fe, Co) catalyze \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reactions, implying Fe/Ni minerals could assist Strecker routes. Quantitative yields for valine itself were not given, but amino acids including glycine/alanine were coproduced[4].\n\u2022\tCyanosulfidic photochemistry: Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) explicitly demonstrated steps toward valine. They showed that UV irradiation of acetone cyanohydrin derivatives with NH\u2083 yields valine aminonitrile 27, with ~42% isolated yield from intermediate 26[5]. The full cascade from glyceraldehyde to 27 was mapped out (Table 1) and validated by NMR and GC (see supplementary figs in [5]). This is strong proof-of-concept for the \u201cHCN + H\u2082S + UV\u201d pathway.\n\u2022\tReductive amination (Kaur et al., 2024, Chem): Kaur and coworkers reported that Ni or meteorite catalysts convert six \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) to amino acids at room temp and pH 8. They measured yields by NMR: with Ni, valine (from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) appeared at ~10\u201350% yield alongside hydroxy acids[10]. Using Pd gave even higher amino acid yields (80\u201390%). Control experiments (no metal, no H\u2082) gave no reaction[10]. This demonstrates that H\u2082-driven amino acid formation is experimentally viable.\n\u2022\tPHOTOCHEMICAL AND OTHER LAB STUDIES: Although not specific to valine, many \u201cMiller\u2010type\u201d experiments under UV or spark conditions produce alanine and often minor valine. For example, glow-discharge on H\u2082\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082 can make amino acids if NH\u2083 or N-containing species are added. No single experiment has targeted valine exclusively, but dozens of studies (reviewed in Patel 2015, Cleaves 2018, Hud 2020) show that branched amino acids can form in mixtures of simple precursors under plausible prebiotic conditions[1][2]. Yields tend to be lower than for glycine/alanine, often <1%.\nIn sum, laboratory evidence supports every step in the proposed pathways. Aminonitriles analogous to valine\u2019s have been isolated; dehydration/hydrolysis steps are well understood; and catalysts (Ni, Cu, Zn) accelerate relevant bond formations. Quantitative data: for Strecker, reported aminonitrile yields from simple aldehydes (e.g. glycine precursor) exceed 50% under optimized conditions[3]; for the photochemical chain, intermediate yields ranged 40\u201370% per step[7]; for reductive amination, valine yields up to ~50% in multi-step mixtures[10]. Although absolute yields vary widely with conditions, these experiments confirm that valine can be synthesized from prebiotic feedstocks.\nEnvironmental Context\nDifferent steps favor different prebiotic environments. Tidal Flats/Evaporitic Basins: Sites with alternating wet/dry cycles concentrate salts and organics (HCN, aldehydes). Sutherland\u2019s cyanosulfidic chemistry is envisioned in shallow \u201cponds\u201d fed by streams carrying ferrocyanide salts[14]. UV light drives key reactions (cyanohydrin formation, photoreduction) in sunlit pools. Sequential merging of streams (with different chemistries) helps deliver reagents stepwise[18][16]. Meteorite impacts could create localized HCN and phosphate (via schreibersite), which upon dissolution feed these basins[14].\nAlkaline Hydrothermal Vents: These are rich in H\u2082, NH\u2083 (from serpentinization or volcanism), and metal sulfides (FeS, NiS). The reductive amination route is most plausible here. Temperatures of 50\u2013150\u202f\u00b0C and high pressures (1\u2013100 bar) are typical. Kaur et al. used mild conditions (22\u202f\u00b0C, 5 bar H\u2082) to mimic cold vent effluent; higher T (50\u2013100\u202f\u00b0C) might even accelerate reactions further. Confinement in mineral pores (e.g. green rust chimneys) could concentrate reactants. Some have suggested fumarolic volcanoes (with H\u2082S) for the photoredox steps as well, but UV is lacking in deep vents.\nAtmosphere and Lightning: Early Earth volcanic eruptions and lightning would produce HCN and small aldehydes in the atmosphere. The classic Miller setup mimics this, with electrical discharge providing energy. Rainout deposits the amino acids into pools. Johnson et al. note: \u201can intense barrage of lightning\u2026 accompanied by eruptions, followed by precipitation\u201d could produce a prebiotic soup containing valine[19]. HCN generated in the atmosphere could also dissolve in oceans or lakes (e.g. forming ferrocyanides[14]), seeding other chemistries.\nIce and Cryoenvironments: Cold regions (ice eutectics) can concentrate solutes and allow slow chemistry. Some experiments show HCN polymerization or amino acid stability in ice, but branched amino acid synthesis specifically has not been demonstrated in ice. Nonetheless, impacts on icy bodies (comets) and icy terrains may be minor sources of amino acids that include valine.\nIn practice, a combination is likely: for example, UV\u2010irradiated streams might produce valine nitrile which is then washed into geothermal pools where hydrolysis and further chemistry occur. The fact that valine is found in meteorites (along with other amino acids) suggests that similar chemistries occurred on asteroid parent bodies, which can be seen as analogs of hydrothermal or UV\u2010irradiated environments.\nOpen Questions and Challenges\nDespite these advances, many aspects remain unresolved. Source of the Branched Precursor: All known routes require C\u2084 or C\u2085 precursors (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate). It is unclear how these were supplied prebiotically. Acetone formation (needed in Patel\u2019s route) is shown, but obtaining sufficient isobutyraldehyde in early Earth settings is speculative. Similarly, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate must arise from prior synthesis (e.g. reductive aldol of glyoxylate and ketone) or contamination. Identifying an efficient abiotic source of these specific precursors is a key gap.\npH and Chemical Constraints: Traditional Strecker synthesis requires high pH or masked ammonia[3], which may not coincide with HCN stability (HCN is volatile at high pH). While DAP circumvents this, DAP itself must be generated (likely from wet-dry cycling of meteorite phosphides). Cyanosulfidic chemistry demands careful timing of reagents (HCN, H\u2082S, phosphate)[16]; how natural environments could orchestrate these pulses (stream merger vs. single\u2010pot) is debated.\nCompetition and Side Reactions: Valine synthesis competes with formation of simpler amino acids, nitriles and polymeric organics. In Miller-type mixtures, glycine/alanine dominate, and branched amino acids are minor. In photochemical networks, many intermediates are lost to side products (e.g. elemental sulfur, HCN polymers). Thus yields of valine in realistic mixtures may be very low, raising the question of whether it would have reached useful concentrations. Some studies have noted poor selectivity (e.g. pantoic vs. glycine formation[4]).\nThermodynamics and Kinetics: The free-energy landscape of these reactions is not fully mapped. For example, the Strecker condensation of a ketone (isobutyraldehyde) with NH\u2083 and HCN is less favorable than for an aldehyde (like glyoxylate). Reductive amination of keto acids is exergonic with H\u2082, but if H\u2082 is limited the reaction may stall. Detailed thermodynamic data for branched amino acid formation under early Earth conditions are sparse.\nHomochirality: All prebiotic routes produce racemic valine (as seen in meteorites). The origin of L-valine in biology is separate (likely via chiral catalysts or selective degradation). However, the lack of any enantiomeric bias in these syntheses is a challenge for explaining life\u2019s L\u2010preference. (Isovaline in meteorites shows some L\u2010excess, but valine is usually racemic, suggesting even if delivered, an enantiomeric excess likely arose later.)\nExperimental Limitations: Many proposed steps have been shown in isolation or under idealized lab conditions. It remains to combine these steps in more realistic, multi-step \u201cone-pot\u201d simulations. For example, no experiment has yet converted HCN all the way to valine in a single simulated pond. Also, geological plausibility (e.g. continuous H\u2082 supply or UV flux) needs further assessment.\nIn summary, the biggest challenges are supplying the correct carbon backbone (branch points) and integrating steps under a coherent early Earth scenario. While several credible pathways to valine exist[2][5][10], no single route is fully proven in a fully prebiotic setting. Resolving these open questions\u2014especially precursor availability and yield limitations\u2014will be crucial for understanding valine\u2019s origin on the prebiotic Earth.\nSources: Peer-reviewed studies (Miller & Schlesinger 1993[2]; Patel et al. 2015[5]; Kaur et al. 2024[10]; Powner et al. 2019[3]; Johnson et al. 2009[1]) and origin-of-life reviews.[5][10][3][2][1]\n \n[1] [19] The Diversity of the Original Prebiotic Soup: Re-analyzing the Original Miller-Urey Spark Discharge Experiments - ADS\nhttps://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2009OLEB...39..240J/abstract\n[2] [4] Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid, pantothenic acid, and the composition of coenzyme A - PubMed\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11536535/\n[3] Selective prebiotic synthesis of phosphoroaminonitriles and aminothioamides in neutral water | Communications Chemistry\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s42004-019-0124-5?error=cookies_not_supported&code=ab3c0682-3751-4eed-af88-0eb76a495a8b\n[5] [6] [7] [8] [9] [11] [12] [13] [14] [16] [18]  Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\n[10] [15]  A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7616004/\n[17] The adsorption of valine on cation-exchanged montmorillonites - DOI\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.clay.2003.08.004\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.65,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \