e\": 0.78,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"A clean, well-supported short pathway. The classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde is directly cited by Miller & Schlesinger (1993). Assumes isobutyraldehyde is pre-formed, which is the central challenge acknowledged in the literature. The environmental progression is limited (Surface \u2192 Biochemical only), but the chemistry is robust. Hydrolysis of valinonitrile is straightforward.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly connect to upstream isobutyraldehyde generation for full pathway credit\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Follows the terminal steps of Patel et al.'s cyanosulfidic pathway from isobutyraldehyde. The ammonolysis step (rxn_010) yielded ~42% in the original paper. Like P7, assumes pre-formed isobutyraldehyde. All three reactions are well-characterized experimentally.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Combine with upstream pathway for complete provenance\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.90\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.90,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.58,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n            \"feedback\": \"Directly supported by Kaur et al. 2024 with Ni catalyst, 5 bar H\u2082, NH\u2084HCO\u2083, 22\u00b0C. Excellent chemistry but as a single-step pathway it assumes \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available. The reaction itself is one of the best-documented in the network. Environmental context (hydrothermal) is appropriate.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Connect to an upstream \u03b1-ketoisovalerate source for a complete pathway\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.65,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.87,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n            \"feedback\": \"The most comprehensive pathway showing full environmental progression from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface cyanosulfidic photochemistry to final product. The acetone hub is well-justified by Patel et al.'s scheme. Multiple convergent sub-pathways (Strecker and ammonolysis) merge at valinonitrile. This is the showcase pathway of the network, demonstrating the full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression with mineral catalysts specified at each stage.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify mineral catalyst for rxn_003 (e.g., borate minerals for formose stabilization)\", \"Consider adding a borate-stabilized formose variant to improve glyceraldehyde yield\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an excellent synthesis network for prebiotic valine that integrates all four major literature-validated routes: (1) Patel et al. cyanosulfidic photochemistry, (2) classical Strecker synthesis, (3) Kaur et al. reductive amination, and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge. The network demonstrates strong topology with 22 molecules, 19 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points. Key strengths include: correct identification of acetone origin from photoreduction of DHA (not pyruvate decarboxylation), proper distinction between acetaldehyde and acetone, faithful representation of Patel et al.'s stepwise cyanohydrin/ammonolysis chemistry, and inclusion of the Kaur et al. Ni-catalyzed reductive amination. The primary weaknesses are: (a) rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde on magnetite) is thermodynamically challenging, (b) rxn_013 (reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is speculative and not experimentally demonstrated, and (c) the Miller-Urey pathway (P5) is chemically valid but mechanistically opaque. The environmental flow is well-designed with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface photochemistry and converging on biochemical-regime hydrolysis. Most hydrothermal reactions appropriately specify mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, Ni). The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014essentially all cited papers (Patel 2015, Miller & Schlesinger 1993, Kaur 2024, Johnson 2009, Powner 2019) are represented in the network. The network also correctly identifies the key open challenge noted in the literature: the prebiotic supply of the branched C\u2084 skeleton (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate).\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n   