ndemonstrated. The pathway nicely stays within the hydrothermal/biochemical transition, which is appropriate for this metabolism-first style chemistry.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_019"], "suggestions": ["Strengthen the \u03b1-ketoisovalerate source", "Consider whether pyridoxamine or metal-ion catalysis could enable transamination"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.8}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.78, "environmental_progression": 0.68, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "A clean, well-supported short pathway. The classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde is directly cited by Miller & Schlesinger (1993). Assumes isobutyraldehyde is pre-formed, which is the central challenge acknowledged in the literature. The environmental progression is limited (Surface \u2192 Biochemical only), but the chemistry is robust. Hydrolysis of valinonitrile is straightforward.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Explicitly connect to upstream isobutyraldehyde generation for full pathway credit"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_010": 0.85, "rxn_012": 0.8}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.8, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "Follows the terminal steps of Patel et al.'s cyanosulfidic pathway from isobutyraldehyde. The ammonolysis step (rxn_010) yielded ~42% in the original paper. Like P7, assumes pre-formed isobutyraldehyde. All three reactions are well-characterized experimentally.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Combine with upstream pathway for complete provenance"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_014": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.9, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.58, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.75, "feedback": "Directly supported by Kaur et al. 2024 with Ni catalyst, 5 bar H\u2082, NH\u2084HCO\u2083, 22\u00b0C. Excellent chemistry but as a single-step pathway it assumes \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available. The reaction itself is one of the best-documented in the network. Environmental context (hydrothermal) is appropriate.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Connect to an upstream \u03b1-ketoisovalerate source for a complete pathway"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.65, "rxn_003": 0.8, "rxn_004": 0.85, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.85, "rxn_007": 0.9, "rxn_008": 0.8, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_010": 0.85, "rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.8}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.87, "environmental_progression": 0.87, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.86, "feedback": "The most comprehensive pathway showing full environmental progression from hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation through surface cyanosulfidic photochemistry to final product. The acetone hub is well-justified by Patel et al.'s scheme. Multiple convergent sub-pathways (Strecker and ammonolysis) merge at valinonitrile. This is the showcase pathway of the network, demonstrating the full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical progression with mineral catalysts specified at each stage.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Specify mineral catalyst for rxn_003 (e.g., borate minerals for formose stabilization)", "Consider adding a borate-stabilized formose variant to improve glyceraldehyde yield"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.86, "network_feedback": "This is an excellent synthesis network for prebiotic valine that integrates all four major literature-validated routes: (1) Patel et al. cyanosulfidic photochemistry, (2) classical Strecker synthesis, (3) Kaur et al. reductive amination, and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge. The network demonstrates strong topology with 22 molecules, 19 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points. Key strengths include: correct identification of acetone origin from photoreduction of DHA (not pyruvate decarboxylation), proper distinction between acetaldehyde and acetone, faithful representation of Patel et al.'s stepwise cyanohydrin/ammonolysis chemistry, and inclusion of the Kaur et al. Ni-catalyzed reductive amination. The primary weaknesses are: (a) rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde on magnetite) is thermodynamically challenging, (b) rxn_013 (reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is speculative and not experimentally demonstrated, and (c) the Miller-Urey pathway (P5) is chemically valid but mechanistically opaque. The environmental flow is well-designed with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface photochemistry and converging on biochemical-regime hydrolysis. Most hydrothermal reactions appropriately specify mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, Ni). The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014essentially all cited papers (Patel 2015, Miller & Schlesinger 1993, Kaur 2024, Johnson 2009, Powner 2019) are represented in the network. The network also correctly identifies the key open challenge noted in the literature: the prebiotic supply of the branched C\u2084 skeleton (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate).", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.91, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 285418.9031124115, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T03:27:34.282971", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis Routes to Valine\nSeveral pathways have been proposed for abiotic valine formation. Classical Miller\u2013Urey\u2013type spark\u2010discharge experiments with a reducing gas mixture (H\u2082, CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082O) generate dozens of amino acids; reanalysis of Miller\u2019s original samples detected valine (and its diastereomer isovaline) among dozens of products[1]. In these electric\u2010discharge experiments, the atmosphere is heated to ~800\u20131200\u202f\u00b0C in brief sparks and cooled, giving rise to Strecker\u2010type chemistry (see below). Valine is only a minor product under such conditions (glycine/alanine dominate), but its presence shows branched amino acids can arise from simple feedstocks[1].\nThe canonical Strecker synthesis is another obvious route: an aldehyde or ketone reacts with NH\u2083 and HCN to give an \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to an amino acid. For valine this requires isobutyraldehyde (2\u2011methylpropanal, (CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) as the carbonyl. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) noted that \u201cisobutyraldehyde is the Strecker precursor to valine\u201d, while \u03b1\u2011ketoisovaleric acid (the transamination product of valine) also participates in these networks[2]. In practice, Strecker routes likely require high pH (because NH\u2083 has pK_aH\u22489.2)[3] and concentrated cyanide. Recent work shows that diamidophosphate (DAP) can promote Strecker syntheses at neutral pH, giving \u201cN\u2011phosphoro\u2011aminonitriles\u201d in high yield (73\u2013quantitative) from simple aldehydes and HCN[3]. By analogy, DAP or related salts could enable valine formation from isobutyraldehyde under mild conditions. However, Strecker reactions select poorly among substrates: Miller & Schlesinger found pantoic acid (from isobutyraldehyde) forms along with glycine, alanine and GABA without selectivity[4]. In summary, Strecker chemistry from isobutyraldehyde\u2009+\u2009NH\u2083\u2009+\u2009HCN is a plausible route to valine via valinonitrile, but it hinges on prebiotic supply of isobutyraldehyde (see Precursors).\nA modern variant is the cyanosulfidic photochemistry first detailed by Patel et al. (2015). In this scheme, HCN is reductively homologated under UV irradiation in the presence of H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox catalysts to build up carbon skeletons. Starting from simpler sugars and cyanide, the chemistry yields \u03b1\u2011aminonitrile precursors of valine (and leucine) via multi\u2010step dark/photochemical cycles. For example, glyceraldehyde and its acetone byproduct are converted (via \u03b1-hydroxythioamides and thioamides) into the cyanohydrin intermediate 26; subsequent addition of NH\u2083 then gives the valine aminonitrile (27)[5][6]. In Patel et al.\u2019s experiments, this 4-step homologation (Fig. 1b) proceeded in ~42% yield of 27[7]. Crucially, this route requires UV irradiation and H\u2082S as reductant; copper sulfide minerals (e.g. cuprous sulfide) can supply Cu(I) and generate HS\u207b from cyanide[8][9]. Thus the cyanosulfidic pathway converges on valine via a Strecker\u2010like aminonitrile, but built up in situ from HCN, small sugars and sulfide.\nA third route is metal\u2010catalyzed reductive amination of keto acids. Kaur et al. (2024) showed that under mild (22\u202f\u00b0C, pH 8) conditions, H\u2082 gas can reduce \u03b1\u2011ketoacids in the presence of NH\u2083 and metal catalysts to yield amino acids[10]. In that work, Ni nanoparticles (and even Ni-bearing meteorite powder) catalyzed H\u2082\u2010driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (the \u03b1\u2011keto acid of valine) into valine[10]. The reactions used 5 bar H\u2082, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, pH 7\u20138 water and 72 h reaction time; with Ni catalysts the combined yield of amino+hydroxy acids was 6\u201384% (valine was one product)[10]. (A Pd catalyst gave higher yields but with >5:1 selectivity of amino acid over the competing \u03b1\u2011hydroxy acid[10].) This \u201cmetabolism\u2010like\u201d hydrogenation network suggests alkaline hydrothermal vent settings (rich in H\u2082 and Ni\u2010Fe minerals) could produce valine by reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.\nOther proposed routes are less studied. For example, generalized formose-type chemistry (polymerization of H\u2082CO) can produce various aldehydes and sugars, but it is not known to yield branched C\u2083 aldehydes efficiently. Similarly, Fischer\u2013Tropsch synthesis on metal sulfides tends to give linear acids (acetate, pyruvate, etc.) rather than branched amino acids. Miller\u2013Urey experiments with added sulfide or formamide have been suggested to improve yields of certain amino acids, but specific valine yields are rarely reported. In summary, the main validated pathways to prebiotic valine are: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde[2], (2) photochemical homologation of HCN[5], (3) H\u2082\u2010driven reductive amination of \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate[10], and (4) complex spark\u2010discharge mixtures[1].\nKey Intermediates and Precursors\nAll known routes rely on larger precursors that embody valine\u2019s branched C\u2083 skeleton. In Strecker chemistry the key intermediate is isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO), which condenses with NH\u2083 and HCN to give valine\u2019s aminonitrile (valinonitrile). Miller & Schlesinger explicitly identified isobutyraldehyde as \u201cthe Strecker precursor to valine\u201d[2]. Similarly, \u03b1\u2011ketoisovalerate (3\u2011methyl\u20112\u2011oxobutanoate) is the immediate precursor in reductive amination routes; it can arise by transamination of valine or by a prior homologation (e.g. as a product of a reductive aldol sequence). In the cyanosulfidic pathway, smaller precursors feed into acetone and acetone derivatives: glyceraldehyde (a C\u2083 sugar) dehydrates/decays partly to dihydroxyacetone (acetone-3, C\u2083) and acetone itself, which then is converted (via thioamide intermediates) to cyanohydrin 26. The \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (formed by NH\u2083 addition) is the penultimate precursor to valine[5]. In all cases the ultimate atom sources are simple C, N, H compounds: HCN, HCHO, NH\u2083, H\u2082, CO\u2082 etc. The key branch\u2011forming steps thus involve either homologation (adding \u2013CH\u2082\u2013 units via HCN chemistry) or decarboxylation of longer keto acids.\nOther precursors can play roles. For example, formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde may polymerize on mineral surfaces to give higher aldols, but branched products are not favored thermodynamically. In the cyanosulfidic route, acetone originates from initial photoredox reduction of dihydroxyacetone (which itself comes from photoredox of glyceraldehyde). Thus dihydroxyacetone (acetone-2) and acetone (acetone-3) are intermediates en route to the valine nitrile[5]. Hydroxylated thioamides (e.g. compounds 24,28 in Patel et al.) and nitriles (26,30) appear transiently in that scheme. Importantly, ammonia (NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a) is a branch precursor (necessary for the \u2013NH\u2082 group in valine) and cyanide (HCN/CN\u207b) provides the \u2013CN unit in aminonitriles; their availability dictates each route\u2019s feasibility. In short, isobutyraldehyde and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate are the largest building blocks needed, while HCN, NH\u2083, H\u2082, formaldehyde, and small sugars are the ubiquitous feedstocks from which these can be assembled.\nReaction Mechanisms and Conditions\nStrecker Synthesis (Chemical Condensation): Isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 valine aminonitrile \u2192 valine after hydrolysis. Mechanistically, the aldehyde first forms an imine with NH\u2083, then CN\u207b adds to give the aminonitrile, which on water\u2010catalyzed hydrolysis yields valine. Conditions reported are aqueous, often neutral\u2010to-basic pH (~8\u201310) because free NH\u2083 is needed[3]. Miller (1993) showed that adding metal salts (Mg\u00b2\u207a, Ca\u00b2\u207a, transition metals) catalyzes reactions of \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) under Strecker-like conditions[2]. Diamidophosphate (DAP) enables the \u201cStrecker\u201d at neutral pH by temporarily masking NH\u2083 and activating HCN/aldehyde[3]. Typical yields depend on concentration and pH; classical Strecker gives roughly 10\u201350% conversion to aminonitrile for favorable substrates, although yields for valine\u2019s nitrile specifically are not routinely reported. One experimental metric: Powner et al. achieved 73\u2013quantitative% yield of N-phosphoro-aminonitriles at pH 7 from simple aldehydes[3] (analogous conditions should work for isobutyraldehyde). After Strecker, heating or acid can hydrolyze the nitrile to the amino acid. The environment is typically a shallow pool or evaporating basin where HCN and NH\u2083 concentrate and ammonia is deprotonated (e.g. volcanic lakes or drying geothermal ponds).\nCyanosulfidic Photoredox (Patel et al. 2015): This multi-step mechanism uses UV light and sulfide. Key steps (Fig. 1b in [5]) are:\n\u2022\tAddition of HCN to ketones: Acetone (formed from glyceraldehyde/dihydroxyacetone) reacts with HCN to give cyanohydrin 23. This is typically reversible, but under the \u201cdark\u201d addition of HS\u207b it converts to an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide (compound 24)[11].\n\u2022\tPhotoreduction: UV light with H\u2082S reductant converts the hydroxylthioamide to a thioamide (25) and further to an aldehyde (byloss of S and H insertion). Continuing UV in H\u2082S + HCN traps the aldehyde as cyanohydrin 26[12].\n\u2022\tAmmonia addition: Finally, NH\u2083 adds to cyanohydrin 26 to yield the \u03b1-aminonitrile 27 (valine precursor)[13].\nConditions were aqueous, UV irradiation (\u2248254 nm or broad UV), presence of H\u2082S (hydrosulfide), phosphate buffer, and catalytic Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on sulfide minerals. Patel et al. carried out these steps in sequence (often with intermediate purification) under room-temperature conditions. Table 1 in [5] shows that converting 26\u219227 gave 42% yield in one step. In practice, overall yields for each homologation step were on the order of tens of percent[5]. Side products include simpler amino acids (alanine, glycine) from parallel pathways, but valine\u2019s pathway was clearly observed. This chemistry is most plausible in sunlit terrestrial ponds with abundant HCN and HS\u207b (e.g. sulfidic lakes or streams after meteorite impacts[14]).\nReductive Amination (Hydrogenation): Kaur et al. demonstrated a straightforward mechanism: an \u03b1-keto acid is hydrogenated and aminated to give the amino acid. For valine, 2-oxoisovalerate + H\u2082 + NH\u2084\u207a \u2192 valine + H\u2082O. This is essentially the reverse of branched amino acid dehydrogenases. They used metallic catalysts (10 mol% Ni or Pd on support) or Ni-rich meteorite powder, 5 bar H\u2082 gas, 150 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083, at pH 8 and 22\u202f\u00b0C[15]. After 72 h, Ni catalysts yielded mixtures of valine and a mixture of hydroxy acids (from partial reduction of the ketoacid); overall conversion was 6\u201384% (depending on catalyst), typically ~50% with Ni[10]. Pd catalysts gave higher yields (~80%) and >5:1 selectivity for amino vs hydroxy acids. No reaction occurred without catalyst[10]. Thus, mild alkaline hydrothermal fluids (cool vents or mixing zones) rich in H\u2082 and NH\u2083 could produce valine from keto precursors with Ni/Fe minerals. Yields are high if the ketoacid is available, and the chemistry tolerates neutral to slightly alkaline pH and ambient to moderate temperature.\nSpark and Miller-type Experiments: In these, a gaseous mixture (e.g. 50% CH\u2084, 20% NH\u2083, 30% H\u2082O vapor) is discharged by spark. Products include amino acids, cyanides, and hydrocarbons. Early analyses found glycine, alanine, aspartic acid in mg yield per liter; valine was present at trace levels. Johnson et al. (2009) reported dozens of amino acids, including valine and isovaline, in Miller\u2019s 1953 samples[1]. Quantitative yields for valine weren\u2019t given, but glycine was tens of \u03bcg/mL in the total liquid. Such discharges represent surface/atmospheric conditions (lightning or volcanism).\nEach route has trade-offs in yield and selectivity. Strecker is efficient for many amino acids in one pot, but requires free NH\u2083 (or masked NH\u2083 like DAP) and yields mixtures (glycine, alanine often dominate). Cyanosulfidic chemistry is selective but complex, needing sequential addition of reagents and UV exposure[16]. Hydrogenation gives good selectivity but needs specific keto precursors. In all cases, yields of valine are modest (single-digit to tens of percent per step) and accompanied by by-products.\nMineral Catalysts and Surfaces\nMineral surfaces are central to many proposed valine syntheses. Nickel and Iron Sulfides: Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user famously invoked NiS/FeS as \u201cproto-enzymes.\u201d In Kaur et al.\u2019s experiments, Ni dispersed on silica or FeNi meteorite powder was required[15]. Specifically, Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) and ground Aletai meteorite (18 mol% Ni) were used as H\u2082 hydrogenation catalysts[15]. Natural analogs include pentlandite [(Fe,Ni)\u2089S\u2088] or mackinawite (FeS) in hydrothermal vents, which can reduce CO\u2082 and nitriles. Copper Sulfides: Patel et al. note that Cu\u2082S or covellite could catalyze their photochemical cycles. Cu(I) forms (e.g. chalcopyrite) can facilitate HCN cross-coupling and photoredox; indeed, Cu(I)/Cu(II) on sulfides is a photosensitizer that drives the HCN homologation with H\u2082S[9]. Cu(II) minerals (malachite) might also transiently form, but CuS is key. Pyrite/Greigite: Iron sulfide (FeS\u2082, Fe\u2083S\u2084) surfaces have been shown to catalyze reduction of nitriles and CO\u2082. While specific studies on valine are lacking, FeS/FeS\u2082 could (by analogy to acetate/pyruvate synthesis) facilitate C\u2013N bond formation or HCN polymerization.\nMontmorillonite and Clays: Smectite clays like montmorillonite can concentrate organics and catalyze certain condensations (e.g. amino acid polymerization). They may help align isobutyraldehyde, HCN and NH\u2083 for Strecker synthesis in drying pools, although direct evidence for valine-specific catalysis is scarce. Experiments have shown clay surfaces strongly adsorb amino acids (including valine)[17], which could assist in concentrating them but can also inhibit reactivity.\nOther Minerals: Zn\u00b2\u207a and other divalent cations accelerate Strecker steps (by stabilizing imines)[2]. Transition\u2010metal phosphides (schreibersite, (Fe,Ni)\u2083P) can hydrolyze to yield phosphate and reduced phosphorus (P\u2083\u207b) which may activate feedstocks, though their role for valine is indirect. NiFe alloys (from meteorites) and iron oxides (magnetite, hematite) also feature in origin-of-life scenarios, but no specific valine synthesis has been demonstrated on them.\nIn summary, Ni/Fe sulfide minerals (present in vents and meteorites) and copper sulfides (in terrestrial Hadean environments) are the main catalysts identified for valine precursors[15][9]. Many origin-of-life studies emphasize these minerals for amino\u2010acid chemistry, so they likely played a role in any prebiotic valine formation.\nExperimental Evidence\n\u2022\tMiller\u2013Urey experiments: Stanley Miller\u2019s 1953 spark\u2011discharge (CH\u2084\u2013NH\u2083\u2013H\u2082O) produced amino acids. Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed original residues and found valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids[1]. This confirms branched amino acids can form abiotically. Glycine/alanine dominated quantitatively, so valine\u2019s yield was low (trace ppm in solution), but its presence is significant.\n\u2022\tStrecker experiments: Although classic Strecker syntheses were developed in the lab (mid-19th century), application to prebiotic chemistry was discussed by Or\u00f3 and others. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) showed that heating isobutyraldehyde + NH\u2083 + HCN (in formamide/water) yields pantoic acid, noting isobutyraldehyde\u2019s connection to valine[2]. They reported that metal salts (Mg, Ca, Fe, Co) catalyze \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reactions, implying Fe/Ni minerals could assist Strecker routes. Quantitative yields for valine itself were not given, but amino acids including glycine/alanine were coproduced[4].\n\u2022\tCyanosulfidic photochemistry: Patel et al. (2015, Nat. Chem.) explicitly demonstrated steps toward valine. They showed that UV irradiation of acetone cyanohydrin derivatives with NH\u2083 yields valine aminonitrile 27, with ~42% isolated yield from intermediate 26[5]. The full cascade from glyceraldehyde to 27 was mapped out (Table 1) and validated by NMR and GC (see supplementary figs in [5]). This is strong proof-of-concept for the \u201cHCN + H\u2082S + UV\u201d pathway.\n\u2022\tReductive amination (Kaur et al., 2024, Chem): Kaur and coworkers reported that Ni or meteorite catalysts convert six \u03b1-keto acids (including ketoisovalerate) to amino acids at room temp and pH 8. They measured yields by NMR: with Ni, valine (from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) appeared at ~10\u201350% yield alongside hydroxy acids[10]. Using Pd gave even higher amino acid yields (80\u201390%). Control experiments (no metal, no H\u2082) gave no reaction[10]. This demonstrates that H\u2082-driven amino acid formation is experimentally viable.\n\u2022\tPHOTOCHEMICAL AND OTHER LAB STUDIES: Although not specific to valine, many \u201cMiller\u2010type\u201d experiments under UV or spark conditions produce alanine and often minor valine. For example, glow-discharge on H\u2082\u2013CO\u2082\u2013N\u2082 can make amino acids if NH\u2083 or N-containing species are added. No single experiment has targeted valine exclusively, but dozens of studies (reviewed in Patel 2015, Cleaves 2018, Hud 2020) show that branched amino acids can form in mixtures of simple precursors under plausible prebiotic conditions[1][2]. Yields tend to be lower than for glycine/alanine, often <1%.\nIn sum, laboratory evidence supports every step in the proposed pathways. Aminonitriles analogous to valine\u2019s have been isolated; dehydration/hydrolysis steps are well understood; and catalysts (Ni, Cu, Zn) accelerate relevant bond formations. Quantitative data: for Strecker, reported aminonitrile yields from simple aldehydes (e.g. glycine precursor) exceed 50% under optimized conditions[3]; for the photochemical chain, intermediate yields ranged 40\u201370% per step[7]; for reductive amination, valine yields up to ~50% in multi-step mixtures[10]. Although absolute yields vary widely with conditions, these experiments confirm that valine can be synthesized from prebiotic feedstocks.\nEnvironmental Context\nDifferent steps favor different prebiotic environments. Tidal Flats/Evaporitic Basins: Sites with alternating wet/dry cycles concentrate salts and organics (HCN, aldehydes). Sutherland\u2019s cyanosulfidic chemistry is envisioned in shallow \u201cponds\u201d fed by streams carrying ferrocyanide salts[14]. UV light drives key reactions (cyanohydrin formation, photoreduction) in sunlit pools. Sequential merging of streams (with different chemistries) helps deliver reagents stepwise[18][16]. Meteorite impacts could create localized HCN and phosphate (via schreibersite), which upon dissolution feed these basins[14].\nAlkaline Hydrothermal Vents: These are rich in H\u2082, NH\u2083 (from serpentinization or volcanism), and metal sulfides (FeS, NiS). The reductive amination route is most plausible here. Temperatures of 50\u2013150\u202f\u00b0C and high pressures (1\u2013100 bar) are typical. Kaur et al. used mild conditions (22\u202f\u00b0C, 5 bar H\u2082) to mimic cold vent effluent; higher T (50\u2013100\u202f\u00b0C) might even accelerate reactions further. Confinement in mineral pores (e.g. green rust chimneys) could concentrate reactants. Some have suggested fumarolic volcanoes (with H\u2082S) for the photoredox steps as well, but UV is lacking in deep vents.\nAtmosphere and Lightning: Early Earth volcanic eruptions and lightning would produce HCN and small aldehydes in the atmosphere. The classic Miller setup mimics this, with electrical discharge providing energy. Rainout deposits the amino acids into pools. Johnson et al. note: \u201can intense barrage of lightning\u2026 accompanied by eruptions, followed by precipitation\u201d could produce a prebiotic soup containing valine[19]. HCN generated in the atmosphere could also dissolve in oceans or lakes (e.g. forming ferrocyanides[14]), seeding other chemistries.\nIce and Cryoenvironments: Cold regions (ice eutectics) can concentrate solutes and allow slow chemistry. Some experiments show HCN polymerization or amino acid stability in ice, but branched amino acid synthesis specifically has not been demonstrated in ice. Nonetheless, impacts on icy bodies (comets) and icy terrains may be minor sources of amino acids that include valine.\nIn practice, a combination is likely: for example, UV\u2010irradiated streams might produce valine nitrile which is then washed into geothermal pools where hydrolysis and further chemistry occur. The fact that valine is found in meteorites (along with other amino acids) suggests that similar chemistries occurred on asteroid parent bodies, which can be seen as analogs of hydrothermal or UV\u2010irradiated environments.\nOpen Questions and Challenges\nDespite these advances, many aspects remain unresolved. Source of the Branched Precursor: All known routes require C\u2084 or C\u2085 precursors (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate). It is unclear how these were supplied prebiotically. Acetone formation (needed in Patel\u2019s route) is shown, but obtaining sufficient isobutyraldehyde in early Earth settings is speculative. Similarly, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate must arise from prior synthesis (e.g. reductive aldol of glyoxylate and ketone) or contamination. Identifying an efficient abiotic source of these specific precursors is a key gap.\npH and Chemical Constraints: Traditional Strecker synthesis requires high pH or masked ammonia[3], which may not coincide with HCN stability (HCN is volatile at high pH). While DAP circumvents this, DAP itself must be generated (likely from wet-dry cycling of meteorite phosphides). Cyanosulfidic chemistry demands careful timing of reagents (HCN, H\u2082S, phosphate)[16]; how natural environments could orchestrate these pulses (stream merger vs. single\u2010pot) is debated.\nCompetition and Side Reactions: Valine synthesis competes with formation of simpler amino acids, nitriles and polymeric organics. In Miller-type mixtures, glycine/alanine dominate, and branched amino acids are minor. In photochemical networks, many intermediates are lost to side products (e.g. elemental sulfur, HCN polymers). Thus yields of valine in realistic mixtures may be very low, raising the question of whether it would have reached useful concentrations. Some studies have noted poor selectivity (e.g. pantoic vs. glycine formation[4]).\nThermodynamics and Kinetics: The free-energy landscape of these reactions is not fully mapped. For example, the Strecker condensation of a ketone (isobutyraldehyde) with NH\u2083 and HCN is less favorable than for an aldehyde (like glyoxylate). Reductive amination of keto acids is exergonic with H\u2082, but if H\u2082 is limited the reaction may stall. Detailed thermodynamic data for branched amino acid formation under early Earth conditions are sparse.\nHomochirality: All prebiotic routes produce racemic valine (as seen in meteorites). The origin of L-valine in biology is separate (likely via chiral catalysts or selective degradation). However, the lack of any enantiomeric bias in these syntheses is a challenge for explaining life\u2019s L\u2010preference. (Isovaline in meteorites shows some L\u2010excess, but valine is usually racemic, suggesting even if delivered, an enantiomeric excess likely arose later.)\nExperimental Limitations: Many proposed steps have been shown in isolation or under idealized lab conditions. It remains to combine these steps in more realistic, multi-step \u201cone-pot\u201d simulations. For example, no experiment has yet converted HCN all the way to valine in a single simulated pond. Also, geological plausibility (e.g. continuous H\u2082 supply or UV flux) needs further assessment.\nIn summary, the biggest challenges are supplying the correct carbon backbone (branch points) and integrating steps under a coherent early Earth scenario. While several credible pathways to valine exist[2][5][10], no single route is fully proven in a fully prebiotic setting. Resolving these open questions\u2014especially precursor availability and yield limitations\u2014will be crucial for understanding valine\u2019s origin on the prebiotic Earth.\nSources: Peer-reviewed studies (Miller & Schlesinger 1993[2]; Patel et al. 2015[5]; Kaur et al. 2024[10]; Powner et al. 2019[3]; Johnson et al. 2009[1]) and origin-of-life reviews.[5][10][3][2][1]\n \n[1] [19] The Diversity of the Original Prebiotic Soup: Re-analyzing the Original Miller-Urey Spark Discharge Experiments - ADS\nhttps://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2009OLEB...39..240J/abstract\n[2] [4] Prebiotic syntheses of vitamin coenzymes: II. Pantoic acid, pantothenic acid, and the composition of coenzyme A - PubMed\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11536535/\n[3] Selective prebiotic synthesis of phosphoroaminonitriles and aminothioamides in neutral water | Communications Chemistry\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s42004-019-0124-5?error=cookies_not_supported&code=ab3c0682-3751-4eed-af88-0eb76a495a8b\n[5] [6] [7] [8] [9] [11] [12] [13] [14] [16] [18]  Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4568310/\n[10] [15]  A prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generates amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel - PMC \nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7616004/\n[17] The adsorption of valine on cation-exchanged montmorillonites - DOI\nhttps://doi.org/10.1016/j.clay.2003.08.004\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network that integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine. The network topology is excellent with 18 molecules, 16 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points. Literature alignment is strong: the Patel et al. cyanosulfidic pathway, Kaur et al. reductive amination, Miller-Schlesinger Strecker synthesis, and Johnson et al. spark-discharge chemistry are all properly represented and cited. The environmental flow (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) is well-structured.\n\nHowever, three reactions have significant chemical issues: (1) rxn_006 (pyruvate\u2192acetone) is incorrect\u2014pyruvate decarboxylation yields acetaldehyde, not acetone; (2) rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is a massive oversimplification of a multi-step biosynthetic pathway with no prebiotic precedent as a single reaction; (3) rxn_014 (Fischer-Tropsch \u2192 isobutyraldehyde) overstates FTT selectivity for branched products, which the literature itself acknowledges is unlikely. These errors affect 6 of 10 pathways.\n\nDespite these issues, pathways P1 and P6 (the cyanosulfidic routes) remain chemically sound and well-supported, achieving valine through literature-validated Patel et al. chemistry. The network successfully reaches the target through multiple valid routes. Mineral catalysts should be more explicitly specified for surface reactions (Cu sulfides for photoreduction, borate for formose). Overall, this is a strong network that would benefit from fixing the three problematic reactions.\n- Issues: ['This pathway is critically undermined by rxn_006: thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate (CH3COCOOH) yields acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) + CO2, NOT acetone (CH3COCH3). Acetone requires a C3 + C3 condensation (e.g., via acetoacetate decarboxylation) or a completely different mechanism. This fundamental chemical error invalidates the pathway as written. Downstream steps from acetone onward are fine.', 'Appealingly short, and the terminal reductive amination (rxn_013) is directly supported by Kaur et al. 2024. However, rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is a major oversimplification. Biosynthetically, this requires multiple enzymatic steps: pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 2,3-dihydroxyisovalerate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. As a single prebiotic reaction, it lacks experimental support. The C3 + C1 \u2192 C5 branched product with no intermediates is chemically implausible in one step.', \"An elegant short pathway. The Strecker and hydrolysis steps are well-supported. However, rxn_014 (Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of isobutyraldehyde from CO + H2) is problematic: FTT synthesis on metal sulfides typically favors linear products (methanol, acetate, formate, linear alkanes/alcohols), and branched C4 aldehydes are not favored products. The literature notes that 'Fischer-Tropsch synthesis on metal sulfides tends to give linear acids rather than branched amino acids.' Specificity for isobutyraldehyde is not experimentally demonstrated.\", 'Biologically elegant transamination pathway, with rxn_015 (reductive amination to alanine) and rxn_016 (transamination) both well-precedented. However, the pathway inherits the critical weakness of rxn_012 (pyruvate + formaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate). Transamination (rxn_016) requires pyridoxal-type cofactors or metal ion catalysis prebiotically, which should be specified. The regeneration of pyruvate in rxn_016 is a nice autocatalytic feature.', 'The convergent concept is excellent\u2014two independent routes to acetone merging at rxn_007. However, the pyruvate decarboxylation arm (rxn_006) is chemically incorrect (pyruvate gives acetaldehyde, not acetone), so only the cyanosulfidic arm (via rxn_005) actually contributes valid acetone. This removes the convergence benefit.', 'Good convergence concept with two routes to isobutyraldehyde (cyanosulfidic photoreduction and Fischer-Tropsch). The cyanosulfidic arm is stronger; the FTT arm (rxn_014) is weakly supported for branched products. The Strecker + hydrolysis conclusion is solid.', 'Hybrid pathway that would convert \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to isobutyraldehyde for Strecker synthesis. The concept is interesting but rxn_012 remains the bottleneck. Also unclear how \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is converted to isobutyraldehyde\u2014this reduction/decarboxylation step seems to be missing from the explicit reactions.', 'Ambitious autocatalytic cycle concept linking cyanosulfidic valine production with transamination recycling. While conceptually appealing for proto-metabolic networks, it inherits weaknesses from rxn_012. The cycle is also very long (10 steps), reducing overall yield dramatically. The autocatalytic claim requires that valine (or pyruvate) from the cycle accelerates its own production, which is plausible for the transamination loop but not clearly demonstrated.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.86\n- Feedback: This is an excellent synthesis network for prebiotic valine that integrates all four major literature-validated routes: (1) Patel et al. cyanosulfidic photochemistry, (2) classical Strecker synthesis, (3) Kaur et al. reductive amination, and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge. The network demonstrates strong topology with 22 molecules, 19 reactions, 5 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points. Key strengths include: correct identification of acetone origin from photoreduction of DHA (not pyruvate decarboxylation), proper distinction between acetaldehyde and acetone, faithful representation of Patel et al.'s stepwise cyanohydrin/ammonolysis chemistry, and inclusion of the Kaur et al. Ni-catalyzed reductive amination. The primary weaknesses are: (a) rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde on magnetite) is thermodynamically challenging, (b) rxn_013 (reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is speculative and not experimentally demonstrated, and (c) the Miller-Urey pathway (P5) is chemically valid but mechanistically opaque. The environmental flow is well-designed with hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation feeding into surface photochemistry and converging on biochemical-regime hydrolysis. Most hydrothermal reactions appropriately specify mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, Ni). The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014essentially all cited papers (Patel 2015, Miller & Schlesinger 1993, Kaur 2024, Johnson 2009, Powner 2019) are represented in the network. The network also correctly identifies the key open challenge noted in the literature: the prebiotic supply of the branched C\u2084 skeleton (isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate).\n- Issues: ['Interesting pathway but hindered by the speculative rxn_013 (reductive carboxylation of acetone to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on greigite). While the analogy to pyruvate synthesis from acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 is noted, acetone is a ketone (not an aldehyde) and carboxylation at the \u03b1-position of a ketone to give an \u03b1-keto acid is mechanistically distinct and not experimentally demonstrated. However, the terminal rxn_014 (reductive amination on Ni) is strongly supported by Kaur et al. 2024.', 'This pathway chains two speculative steps: rxn_013 (acetone \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) and rxn_019 (prebiotic transamination). Transamination without pyridoxal phosphate or metal-ion catalysts is slow and low-yielding. While metal-catalyzed transamination has some literature support, the combination of two weak steps significantly lowers confidence. The alanine generation (rxn_018) is well-supported.', \"While Johnson et al. (2009) confirmed valine in Miller's spark discharge products, this is a single-step black-box reaction producing valine only as a trace product among dozens of amino acids. It provides no mechanistic insight and the yield is extremely low (sub-ppm levels). As a network pathway it adds breadth but lacks the stepwise detail expected. The 'Surface' designation for spark discharge is acceptable (atmospheric/lightning simulation).\", 'This pathway depends on both the speculative \u03b1-ketoisovalerate formation and prebiotic transamination. The pyruvate \u2192 alanine branch is solid (Kaur et al.), but the transamination requires \u03b1-ketoisovalerate from rxn_013 which remains undemonstrated. The pathway nicely stays within the hydrothermal/biochemical transition, which is appropriate for this metabolism-first style chemistry.', 'Directly supported by Kaur et al. 2024 with Ni catalyst, 5 bar H\u2082, NH\u2084HCO\u2083, 22\u00b0C. Excellent chemistry but as a single-step pathway it assumes \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available. The reaction itself is one of the best-documented in the network. Environmental context (hydrothermal) is appropriate.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine: (1) Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic photochemistry via glyceraldehyde \u2192 acetone \u2192 valinonitrile, (2) classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, (3) Kaur et al. (2024) Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge. The network traces carbon from CO\u2082 (hydrothermal) and formaldehyde (surface) through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then through two main branches: the cyanosulfidic photoreduction branch yielding acetone/cyanohydrin intermediates, and a cyanohydrin-hydrolysis branch generating \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Five hub molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, acetone, isobutyraldehyde, valinonitrile) create network density. The key open challenge\u2014prebiotic supply of the branched C\u2084 skeleton\u2014is addressed via Patel et al.'s demonstrated acetone-to-isobutyraldehyde cyanosulfidic reduction, and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is generated from isobutyraldehyde through a chemically sound cyanohydrin\u2192hydroxy acid\u2192keto acid sequence.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetone cyanohydrin (compound 23)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-3(2,5)4-6/h5H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanamidothioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-hydroxythioamide (compound 24)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin (compound 26)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valinonitrile (compound 27)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4,6H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H2 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate via surface-bound hydride transfer on greigite (Fe3S4), an analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociatively adsorbs on the Fe-S surface to generate metal-hydride species, which transfer to CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a well-established hydrothermal reaction at alkaline vents. This reaction provides the initial C1 building block for downstream formaldehyde and formose chemistry. Supported by iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988) and demonstrated experimentally for CO2\u2192formate conversion on Fe3S4.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate photoreduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"siderite (FeCO3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 anatase\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), shallow pool receiving hydrothermal outflow\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photons excite TiO2 semiconductor surfaces generating electron-hole pairs. Photoelectrons reduce formate (HCOO\u207b) to formaldehyde (HCHO) + OH\u207b. Siderite may also participate as UV-active mineral for formate photoreduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formate-to-formaldehyde conversion is thermodynamically uphill but photochemically feasible on TiO2 or siderite under UV. This connects hydrothermal C1 products to surface formose chemistry. TiO2 photoreduction of carboxylates is documented in prebiotic contexts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose initiation: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2 and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, formose reaction initiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo umpolung-type self-condensation via the Breslow cycle. Under alkaline conditions with Ca(OH)\u2082, an enolizable formaldehyde tautomer attacks a second HCHO to form glycolaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize sugar products and suppress the Cannizzaro reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formose reaction is a well-established prebiotic pathway from HCHO to sugars. Borate stabilization of sugars is documented by Ricardo et al. (2004). Glycolaldehyde is the initial C2 product and feeds into glyceraldehyde synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline pool, borate complexation directs aldol selectivity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde enolizes under alkaline conditions and attacks formaldehyde electrophilically to give glyceraldehyde (C3). Borate minerals complex with vicinal diols of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing the product against degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde is a standard formose pathway step. Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is critical to prevent degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glyceraldehyde is a key precursor for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone isomerization\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface / base catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"keto-enol tautomerization, equilibrium favors DHA slightly\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes base-catalyzed 1,2-enolization to form the enediol intermediate, which re-protonates at C1 to give dihydroxyacetone (DHA). This is a standard Lobry de Bruyn-van Ekenstein isomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde-DHA interconversion is thermodynamically facile and well-documented. In the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic scheme, glyceraldehyde is converted to DHA as a precursor to acetone. Clay surfaces may catalyze the isomerization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of DHA to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as terminal reductant, phosphate buffer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV light drives Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on copper sulfide surfaces. Cu(I) donates an electron to DHA, reducing the terminal hydroxyls to hydrogen, while H2S provides reducing equivalents (being oxidized to elemental sulfur). Net transformation: HOCH2COCH2OH \u2192 CH3COCH3 + H2O. This is a photoreductive deoxygenation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde/DHA are photoreduced to acetone under UV in the presence of H2S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) catalysis. This is a critical step in the cyanosulfidic pathway, providing the branched C3 ketone needed for valine's isopropyl skeleton. Cu2S minerals serve as the photocatalytic surface (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetone cyanohydrin formation (compound 23)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (spontaneous nucleophilic addition)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"dark reaction, mildly basic pH, HCN/CN\u207b addition to ketone\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone. Protonation of the resulting alkoxide gives acetone cyanohydrin ((CH3)2C(OH)CN, compound 23 in Patel et al.). This is a standard cyanohydrin formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) described the addition of HCN to acetone as the first step in the valine homologation sequence (Fig. 1b). This dark reaction proceeds readily in aqueous solution at near-neutral pH where CN\u207b is available. The cyanohydrin 23 is an established intermediate en route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioamide formation: cyanohydrin 23 to alpha-hydroxythioamide 24\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"H2S/HS\u207b in dark conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"dark reaction, HS\u207b attacks nitrile carbon, Cu sulfide provides sulfide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrosulfide (HS\u207b) performs nucleophilic addition to the nitrile (C\u2261N) of acetone cyanohydrin 23, generating a thioamide functional group. The product is the \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24, retaining the hydroxyl from the cyanohydrin. This sulfide-mediated nitrile hydration is analogous to nitrile hydratase chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this dark-phase conversion of cyanohydrin 23 to \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24 using H2S. Cu sulfide minerals can supply HS\u207b from dissolved copper sulfide or from HCN reduction (Patel et al., 2015). This step activates the nitrile for subsequent photoreduction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreductive homologation: compound 24 to cyanohydrin 26 via compound 25\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), sequential: (i) photoreduction of 24 with H2S to thioamide 25, losing the \u03b1-OH as H2O; (ii) further photoreduction of 25 to an aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde); (iii) immediate HCN trapping of the aldehyde to cyanohydrin 26\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This is a multi-step photochemical sequence within the same UV-irradiated environment. First, UV/H2S photoreduces \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24 to thioamide 25 (removing the OH, replacing with H). Then UV/H2S converts thioamide 25 via desulfurization to the corresponding aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde). HCN present in solution immediately traps this transient aldehyde as cyanohydrin 26 (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). This extends the carbon chain from C4 (acetone + CN) to effectively a C5 skeleton (C4 aldehyde + CN).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated this photoreductive homologation cascade (compounds 24\u219225\u219226) as the key chain-extension step in valine synthesis. UV irradiation with H2S drives sequential reductions on Cu sulfide surfaces. The overall ~42% yield from 26 to 27 (next step) was reported, with intermediate yields of 40-70% per step (Table 1, Patel et al., 2015). This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine's branched skeleton.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonolysis: cyanohydrin 26 to valinonitrile 27\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (NH3 nucleophilic substitution)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"NH3/NH4+ at pH 8-9, displacement of OH by NH2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group of cyanohydrin 26 via an SN2-like or elimination-addition mechanism. The \u03b1-hydroxy nitrile is converted to an \u03b1-amino nitrile (valinonitrile, compound 27). This is effectively the Strecker aminonitrile formation step, but operating on a pre-formed cyanohydrin rather than starting from aldehyde + NH3 + HCN simultaneously.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this conversion with ~42% yield of compound 27 from compound 26 (Table 1). This ammonolysis is the penultimate step before hydrolysis to valine. The reaction requires sufficient NH3 concentration at mildly basic pH, consistent with volcanic/geothermal pool settings. Montmorillonite may concentrate reactants at the surface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation: compound 26 to isobutyraldehyde + HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"base catalysis (OH\u207b)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reversible under slightly basic pH; dissociation favored at higher pH where HCN is deprotonated\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanohydrin 26 undergoes base-catalyzed retro-cyanohydrin reaction: the C-CN bond cleaves heterolytically, releasing CN\u207b and generating isobutyraldehyde ((CH3)2CHCHO). This equilibrium is pH-dependent\u2014at higher pH, CN\u207b deprotonation drives dissociation. The released isobutyraldehyde is a free C4 branched aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation is well-known to be reversible. Compound 26 in Patel et al. (2015) is the cyanohydrin of isobutyraldehyde. Under basic conditions (e.g., pH > 9), the equilibrium shifts toward free aldehyde + CN\u207b. This reaction connects the cyanosulfidic pathway to the Strecker pathway by liberating free isobutyraldehyde, which Miller & Schlesinger (1993) identified as 'the Strecker precursor to valine.' This provides a prebiotically grounded source for isobutyraldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + NH3 + HCN to valinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"Zn2+ minerals (sphalerite ZnS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Zn2+ ions (stabilize imine), clay surfaces concentrate reactants\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10, NH3 must be deprotonated (pKaH ~9.2), evaporitic pool or drying pond\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Step 1: NH3 attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde, forming a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base, (CH3)2CH-CH=NH). Step 2: CN\u207b attacks the electrophilic imine carbon, forming valinonitrile (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile, compound 27). Zn2+ can stabilize the imine intermediate, accelerating CN\u207b addition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Miller & Schlesinger (1993) explicitly identified isobutyraldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor to valine' and noted metal salt catalysis (Mg2+, Ca2+, Fe2+, Co2+, Zn2+) for analogous \u03b1-keto acid reactions. Classical Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest known routes to amino acids from aldehydes. Montmorillonite concentrates and aligns reactants in drying-pool settings. ZnS (sphalerite) provides Zn2+ for imine stabilization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-mediated Strecker synthesis of valinonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (struvite/apatite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"diamidophosphate (DAP) as NH3 activator\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH (~7), DAP enables Strecker at lower pH by forming N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate (DAP) reacts with the aldehyde and HCN, forming an N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate. This activates NH3 transfer and CN\u207b addition at neutral pH, bypassing the requirement for free NH3 (which is mostly protonated at pH 7). The N-phosphoroaminonitrile then hydrolyzes to release valinonitrile and phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Powner et al. (2019, Communications Chemistry) showed that DAP promotes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH with 73-quantitative% yield of N-phosphoroaminonitriles from simple aldehydes + HCN. By analogy, DAP-mediated Strecker from isobutyraldehyde should yield valinonitrile under the same mild conditions. DAP itself can form from wet-dry cycling of meteorite-derived phosphides (schreibersite). Phosphate minerals provide DAP precursor.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Valinonitrile hydrolysis to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"330-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"acid or base catalysis; mineral surfaces optional\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"mild heating in acidic or basic aqueous solution; wet-dry cycling may assist\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of valinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first, water attacks the nitrile carbon to form an amide intermediate (valinamide), which then hydrolyzes further to valine + NH3 (or valine under acidic conditions). The overall transformation: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COOH + NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis is the terminal step in all Strecker-based valine syntheses. Patel et al. (2015) and Miller & Schlesinger (1993) both invoke this step. Nitrile hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously in warm aqueous solutions, especially under acidic or basic conditions. Geothermal heating (50-100\u00b0C) would accelerate this reaction in prebiotic pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin hydrolysis of isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"acid or base catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"isobutyraldehyde + HCN form cyanohydrin in situ, which hydrolyzes to \u03b1-hydroxy acid; two-step one-pot process\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Isobutyraldehyde reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin (identical to compound 26 from Patel pathway). Under acidic or basic aqueous conditions, the nitrile group of this cyanohydrin hydrolyzes (via amide intermediate) to the carboxylic acid, yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid). The \u03b1-OH is retained (unlike the Strecker route where NH3 replaces OH).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanohydrin formation + hydrolysis is the classical route to \u03b1-hydroxy acids, directly paralleling the Strecker route but without NH3. Kaur et al. (2024) noted that \u03b1-hydroxy acids are co-products of reductive amination alongside amino acids, confirming this competing pathway. This provides a prebiotic route to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid, the immediate precursor to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via oxidation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidation of alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid to alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photocatalysis on TiO2; Fe3+ ions from pyrite weathering\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, mild oxidation; Fe3+ acts as one-electron oxidant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-hydroxyl group of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid is oxidized to a ketone, yielding \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid). This can proceed via UV-TiO2 photocatalytic oxidation (generating hydroxyl radicals that selectively abstract the \u03b1-H) or by Fe3+-mediated electron transfer (Fe3+ \u2192 Fe2+ + radical, followed by radical recombination to give the ketone).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"\u03b1-Hydroxy acid to \u03b1-keto acid oxidation is thermodynamically favorable and can be driven by UV photochemistry or Fe3+ oxidation. This provides a prebiotically plausible route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, which Kaur et al. (2024) used as the starting material for reductive amination. The prebiotic source of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is identified as a key open question in the literature; this cyanohydrin hydrolysis \u2192 oxidation route addresses that gap using isobutyraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)9S8)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe sulfide minerals (pentlandite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-8, NH4HCO3 buffer (150 mM), 72h reaction time; Ni-bearing meteorite powder also effective\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2 dissociatively adsorbs on Ni-containing mineral surfaces, generating metal-hydride species. The \u03b1-keto acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate) first forms an imine with NH3 (via condensation of the ketone with ammonia), then the metal-hydride reduces the C=N imine bond to give the amino acid (valine). Competing \u03b1-hydroxy acid formation occurs via direct C=O reduction without NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) demonstrated this reaction explicitly: Ni nanoparticles or FeNi meteorite powder catalyzed H2-driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 5 bar H2. Combined amino + hydroxy acid yields were 6-84% depending on catalyst (Ni gave ~50%). Pd gave 80-90% yield with >5:1 amino:hydroxy selectivity. No reaction occurred without metal catalyst. Natural analogs include pentlandite and awaruite (Ni3Fe) in alkaline hydrothermal vents.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Ni catalyst\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)9S8)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"5 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-8, NH4HCO3, analogous conditions to rxn_017\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate condenses with NH3 to form an imine, which is reduced by H2 on Ni surface to give alanine. Identical mechanism to rxn_017 but with the C3 substrate pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated reductive amination of multiple \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate to the corresponding amino acids. Alanine production from pyruvate is well-established in this system. Alanine serves as an amino group donor for transamination reactions downstream.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Metal-catalyzed transamination: alpha-ketoisovalerate + alanine to valine + pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/Cu2+ ions as Lewis acid catalysts\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"requires metal-ion catalysis for prebiotic transamination; Fe2+ abundant on early Earth; may occur at mineral-water interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine forms a Schiff base with \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (or with a metal-bound pyridoxal analog). The amino group is transferred from alanine to the keto acid via a tautomeric shift through the ketimine-aldimine equilibrium, yielding valine + pyruvate. Fe2+ or Cu2+ coordinates both substrates and lowers the activation barrier for the 1,3-prototropic shift.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination is the biological route to valine (via branched-chain aminotransferase). Prebiotic transamination has been demonstrated with metal-ion catalysts (Fe2+, Cu2+) substituting for pyridoxal phosphate. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) noted that metal salts catalyze \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reactions. This pathway regenerates pyruvate, creating a proto-metabolic cycle. While less efficient than enzymatic transamination, it provides an alternative route to valine when \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine co-occur.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite surface catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent, multiple CO2 reduction steps on mineral surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction on iron oxide/sulfide surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde (via surface-bound intermediates) \u2192 pyruvate via further carboxylation and oxidation. The mineral surface provides a template for stepwise carbon fixation, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 + H2 on iron mineral surfaces has been demonstrated experimentally. Magnetite and greigite catalyze these multi-step reductions at alkaline vent conditions. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub in both biology and prebiotic chemistry. It serves as both a precursor to alanine (via rxn_018) and a transamination product (rxn_019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis of valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"800-1200K (brief spark), then 300K (cooling)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electric discharge (lightning analog); mineral dust (TiO2) may serve as nucleation surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reducing atmosphere: CH4 + NH3 + H2O + H2; spark produces HCN, aldehydes, which undergo Strecker-type chemistry upon cooling and dissolution in water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electric discharge through a reducing gas mixture (CH4, NH3, H2O, H2) fragments molecules into reactive radicals (CH, CH2, NH, CN). Upon cooling, these recombine to form HCN, aldehydes (including trace isobutyraldehyde), and NH3. In the aqueous phase, Strecker-type chemistry converts these to aminonitriles, which hydrolyze to amino acids. Valine is a minor product alongside dominant glycine and alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed Miller's original 1953 spark-discharge samples and detected valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids. While valine is only a trace product (glycine/alanine dominate), its presence confirms that branched amino acids can arise from simple reducing gas mixtures under spark-discharge conditions. This represents an atmospheric/lightning route to valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN synthesis from methane and nitrogen\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"800-1200K (lightning/UV), 300K (ambient)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photolysis or electrical discharge\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"atmospheric chemistry; CH4 + N sources (NH3, N2) \u2192 HCN via radical reactions; HCN dissolves in rain and accumulates in surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV photolysis or lightning discharge fragments CH4 into CH and CH2 radicals, and NH3 into NH radicals. CH + NH recombine to form HCN. Alternatively, N2 + CH4 under strong UV or discharge yields HCN directly. HCN accumulates in the atmosphere and dissolves in rainwater, concentrating in surface pools and lakes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Atmospheric HCN production is a well-established source of prebiotic cyanide. HCN is the critical C1/N building block for both Strecker synthesis and cyanosulfidic chemistry. Miller-Urey experiments demonstrate HCN as a primary product of spark discharge (Johnson et al., 2009). HCN dissolved in surface water feeds into all downstream cyanide-dependent pathways.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full Patel cyanosulfidic pathway (formose to valine)\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete cyanosulfidic route starting from formaldehyde through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then photoreduction to acetone, followed by Patel et al.'s (2015) four-step homologation to valinonitrile, ending with hydrolysis to valine. This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic pathway to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 to cyanosulfidic valine (cross-environment)\",\n      \"description\": \"Starting from hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate, then surface photoreduction to formaldehyde, entering the formose/cyanosulfidic cascade to valine. Demonstrates Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde to classical Strecker\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic pathway generates cyanohydrin 26, which undergoes reversible dissociation to release free isobutyraldehyde. This aldehyde then enters classical Strecker synthesis (isobutyraldehyde + NH3 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile \u2192 valine). Connects Patel photochemistry with Miller-Schlesinger Strecker route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-mediated Strecker at neutral pH\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde (from cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin dissociation) undergoes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH mediated by diamidophosphate (DAP), as demonstrated by Powner et al. (2019). This route overcomes the pH constraint of classical Strecker (which needs pH > 9 for free NH3).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Kaur reductive amination from cyanosulfidic \u03b1-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic pathway is converted to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid (via cyanohydrin hydrolysis), then oxidized to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and finally reduced to valine by H2 on Ni minerals. This connects Patel's surface chemistry to Kaur et al.'s hydrothermal reductive amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination (shortest from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate)\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with H2 and NH3 on Ni catalyst, as demonstrated by Kaur et al. (2024). This is the most direct route when \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available, requiring only one reaction step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination pathway via alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis, followed by reductive amination to alanine (on Ni), then metal-catalyzed transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine to yield valine + pyruvate. This creates a proto-metabolic autocatalytic cycle where pyruvate is regenerated.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cross-environment transamination (Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical)\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is fixed to pyruvate hydrothermally; pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine. In parallel, the cyanosulfidic surface pathway generates isobutyraldehyde, which is converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via cyanohydrin hydrolysis and oxidation. Alanine and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate then undergo transamination to valine in the biochemical regime.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_020\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Miller-Urey spark discharge to valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical Miller-Urey atmospheric chemistry: electric discharge through a reducing gas mixture (CH4, NH3, H2O, H2) produces valine as a minor product among dozens of amino acids. As confirmed by Johnson et al. (2009) reanalysis of Miller's original 1953 samples.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN to cyanosulfidic valine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is generated atmospherically from CH4 and N-sources, dissolves in surface waters, and drives the cyanosulfidic pathway: HCN provides both the cyanohydrin carbon and the aminonitrile nitrogen. This pathway traces HCN from its atmospheric source through all cyanosulfidic intermediates to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_022\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"description\": \"Valinonitrile (compound 27) - convergence point for three aminonitrile-forming reactions\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde - the branched C4 aldehyde hub connecting cyanosulfidic to Strecker and reductive amination pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetone - the key branched C3 ketone formed by photoreduction of DHA, feeding all cyanosulfidic downstream chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoisovalerate - convergence point for oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid, feeding both reductive amination and transamination\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN - central nitrogen/carbon building block used in cyanohydrin formation, Strecker synthesis, and cyanosulfidic homologation\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine", "overall_strategy": "This network integrates four literature-validated prebiotic routes to valine: (1) Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic photochemistry via glyceraldehyde \u2192 acetone \u2192 valinonitrile, (2) classical Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, (3) Kaur et al. (2024) Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and (4) Miller-Urey spark discharge. The network traces carbon from CO\u2082 (hydrothermal) and formaldehyde (surface) through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then through two main branches: the cyanosulfidic photoreduction branch yielding acetone/cyanohydrin intermediates, and a cyanohydrin-hydrolysis branch generating \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. Five hub molecules (HCN, NH\u2083, acetone, isobutyraldehyde, valinonitrile) create network density. The key open challenge\u2014prebiotic supply of the branched C\u2084 skeleton\u2014is addressed via Patel et al.'s demonstrated acetone-to-isobutyraldehyde cyanosulfidic reduction, and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is generated from isobutyraldehyde through a chemically sound cyanohydrin\u2192hydroxy acid\u2192keto acid sequence.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O", "iupac_name": "propan-2-one", "common_name": "acetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile", "common_name": "acetone cyanohydrin (compound 23)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-3(2,5)4-6/h5H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9NOS", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanamidothioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-hydroxythioamide (compound 24)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin (compound 26)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-3(2)4(7)5-6/h3-4,7H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valinonitrile (compound 27)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H10O3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4,6H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H2 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is reduced to formate via surface-bound hydride transfer on greigite (Fe3S4), an analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociatively adsorbs on the Fe-S surface to generate metal-hydride species, which transfer to CO2.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a well-established hydrothermal reaction at alkaline vents. This reaction provides the initial C1 building block for downstream formaldehyde and formose chemistry. Supported by iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988) and demonstrated experimentally for CO2\u2192formate conversion on Fe3S4."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate photoreduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "siderite (FeCO3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 anatase", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), shallow pool receiving hydrothermal outflow"}, "mechanism": "UV photons excite TiO2 semiconductor surfaces generating electron-hole pairs. Photoelectrons reduce formate (HCOO\u207b) to formaldehyde (HCHO) + OH\u207b. Siderite may also participate as UV-active mineral for formate photoreduction.", "reasoning": "Formate-to-formaldehyde conversion is thermodynamically uphill but photochemically feasible on TiO2 or siderite under UV. This connects hydrothermal C1 products to surface formose chemistry. TiO2 photoreduction of carboxylates is documented in prebiotic contexts."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formose initiation: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2 and borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, formose reaction initiation"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo umpolung-type self-condensation via the Breslow cycle. Under alkaline conditions with Ca(OH)\u2082, an enolizable formaldehyde tautomer attacks a second HCHO to form glycolaldehyde. Borate minerals stabilize sugar products and suppress the Cannizzaro reaction.", "reasoning": "Formose reaction is a well-established prebiotic pathway from HCHO to sugars. Borate stabilization of sugars is documented by Ricardo et al. (2004). Glycolaldehyde is the initial C2 product and feeds into glyceraldehyde synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation: glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline pool, borate complexation directs aldol selectivity"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde enolizes under alkaline conditions and attacks formaldehyde electrophilically to give glyceraldehyde (C3). Borate minerals complex with vicinal diols of glyceraldehyde, stabilizing the product against degradation.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde is a standard formose pathway step. Borate stabilization of glyceraldehyde is critical to prevent degradation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glyceraldehyde is a key precursor for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone isomerization", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface / base catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "keto-enol tautomerization, equilibrium favors DHA slightly"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes base-catalyzed 1,2-enolization to form the enediol intermediate, which re-protonates at C1 to give dihydroxyacetone (DHA). This is a standard Lobry de Bruyn-van Ekenstein isomerization.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde-DHA interconversion is thermodynamically facile and well-documented. In the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic scheme, glyceraldehyde is converted to DHA as a precursor to acetone. Clay surfaces may catalyze the isomerization."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoreduction of DHA to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox on sulfide minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), H2S as terminal reductant, phosphate buffer"}, "mechanism": "UV light drives Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling on copper sulfide surfaces. Cu(I) donates an electron to DHA, reducing the terminal hydroxyls to hydrogen, while H2S provides reducing equivalents (being oxidized to elemental sulfur). Net transformation: HOCH2COCH2OH \u2192 CH3COCH3 + H2O. This is a photoreductive deoxygenation.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated that glyceraldehyde/DHA are photoreduced to acetone under UV in the presence of H2S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) catalysis. This is a critical step in the cyanosulfidic pathway, providing the branched C3 ketone needed for valine's isopropyl skeleton. Cu2S minerals serve as the photocatalytic surface (Patel et al., 2015, Nature Chemistry)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Acetone cyanohydrin formation (compound 23)", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (spontaneous nucleophilic addition)", "aqueous": true, "other": "dark reaction, mildly basic pH, HCN/CN\u207b addition to ketone"}, "mechanism": "Cyanide anion (CN\u207b) acts as a nucleophile attacking the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone. Protonation of the resulting alkoxide gives acetone cyanohydrin ((CH3)2C(OH)CN, compound 23 in Patel et al.). This is a standard cyanohydrin formation.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) described the addition of HCN to acetone as the first step in the valine homologation sequence (Fig. 1b). This dark reaction proceeds readily in aqueous solution at near-neutral pH where CN\u207b is available. The cyanohydrin 23 is an established intermediate en route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Thioamide formation: cyanohydrin 23 to alpha-hydroxythioamide 24", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "H2S/HS\u207b in dark conditions", "aqueous": true, "other": "dark reaction, HS\u207b attacks nitrile carbon, Cu sulfide provides sulfide"}, "mechanism": "Hydrosulfide (HS\u207b) performs nucleophilic addition to the nitrile (C\u2261N) of acetone cyanohydrin 23, generating a thioamide functional group. The product is the \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24, retaining the hydroxyl from the cyanohydrin. This sulfide-mediated nitrile hydration is analogous to nitrile hydratase chemistry.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this dark-phase conversion of cyanohydrin 23 to \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24 using H2S. Cu sulfide minerals can supply HS\u207b from dissolved copper sulfide or from HCN reduction (Patel et al., 2015). This step activates the nitrile for subsequent photoreduction."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Photoreductive homologation: compound 24 to cyanohydrin 26 via compound 25", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["copper sulfide (Cu2S/CuS)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), sequential: (i) photoreduction of 24 with H2S to thioamide 25, losing the \u03b1-OH as H2O; (ii) further photoreduction of 25 to an aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde); (iii) immediate HCN trapping of the aldehyde to cyanohydrin 26"}, "mechanism": "This is a multi-step photochemical sequence within the same UV-irradiated environment. First, UV/H2S photoreduces \u03b1-hydroxythioamide 24 to thioamide 25 (removing the OH, replacing with H). Then UV/H2S converts thioamide 25 via desulfurization to the corresponding aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde). HCN present in solution immediately traps this transient aldehyde as cyanohydrin 26 (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). This extends the carbon chain from C4 (acetone + CN) to effectively a C5 skeleton (C4 aldehyde + CN).", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated this photoreductive homologation cascade (compounds 24\u219225\u219226) as the key chain-extension step in valine synthesis. UV irradiation with H2S drives sequential reductions on Cu sulfide surfaces. The overall ~42% yield from 26 to 27 (next step) was reported, with intermediate yields of 40-70% per step (Table 1, Patel et al., 2015). This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine's branched skeleton."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Ammonolysis: cyanohydrin 26 to valinonitrile 27", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (NH3 nucleophilic substitution)", "aqueous": true, "other": "NH3/NH4+ at pH 8-9, displacement of OH by NH2"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group of cyanohydrin 26 via an SN2-like or elimination-addition mechanism. The \u03b1-hydroxy nitrile is converted to an \u03b1-amino nitrile (valinonitrile, compound 27). This is effectively the Strecker aminonitrile formation step, but operating on a pre-formed cyanohydrin rather than starting from aldehyde + NH3 + HCN simultaneously.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated this conversion with ~42% yield of compound 27 from compound 26 (Table 1). This ammonolysis is the penultimate step before hydrolysis to valine. The reaction requires sufficient NH3 concentration at mildly basic pH, consistent with volcanic/geothermal pool settings. Montmorillonite may concentrate reactants at the surface."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation: compound 26 to isobutyraldehyde + HCN", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "base catalysis (OH\u207b)", "aqueous": true, "other": "reversible under slightly basic pH; dissociation favored at higher pH where HCN is deprotonated"}, "mechanism": "Cyanohydrin 26 undergoes base-catalyzed retro-cyanohydrin reaction: the C-CN bond cleaves heterolytically, releasing CN\u207b and generating isobutyraldehyde ((CH3)2CHCHO). This equilibrium is pH-dependent\u2014at higher pH, CN\u207b deprotonation drives dissociation. The released isobutyraldehyde is a free C4 branched aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation is well-known to be reversible. Compound 26 in Patel et al. (2015) is the cyanohydrin of isobutyraldehyde. Under basic conditions (e.g., pH > 9), the equilibrium shifts toward free aldehyde + CN\u207b. This reaction connects the cyanosulfidic pathway to the Strecker pathway by liberating free isobutyraldehyde, which Miller & Schlesinger (1993) identified as 'the Strecker precursor to valine.' This provides a prebiotically grounded source for isobutyraldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis: isobutyraldehyde + NH3 + HCN to valinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "Zn2+ minerals (sphalerite ZnS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Zn2+ ions (stabilize imine), clay surfaces concentrate reactants", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8-10, NH3 must be deprotonated (pKaH ~9.2), evaporitic pool or drying pond"}, "mechanism": "Step 1: NH3 attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde, forming a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base, (CH3)2CH-CH=NH). Step 2: CN\u207b attacks the electrophilic imine carbon, forming valinonitrile (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile, compound 27). Zn2+ can stabilize the imine intermediate, accelerating CN\u207b addition.", "reasoning": "Miller & Schlesinger (1993) explicitly identified isobutyraldehyde as 'the Strecker precursor to valine' and noted metal salt catalysis (Mg2+, Ca2+, Fe2+, Co2+, Zn2+) for analogous \u03b1-keto acid reactions. Classical Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest known routes to amino acids from aldehydes. Montmorillonite concentrates and aligns reactants in drying-pool settings. ZnS (sphalerite) provides Zn2+ for imine stabilization."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "DAP-mediated Strecker synthesis of valinonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (struvite/apatite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate (DAP) as NH3 activator", "aqueous": true, "other": "neutral pH (~7), DAP enables Strecker at lower pH by forming N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Diamidophosphate (DAP) reacts with the aldehyde and HCN, forming an N-phosphoroaminonitrile intermediate. This activates NH3 transfer and CN\u207b addition at neutral pH, bypassing the requirement for free NH3 (which is mostly protonated at pH 7). The N-phosphoroaminonitrile then hydrolyzes to release valinonitrile and phosphate.", "reasoning": "Powner et al. (2019, Communications Chemistry) showed that DAP promotes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH with 73-quantitative% yield of N-phosphoroaminonitriles from simple aldehydes + HCN. By analogy, DAP-mediated Strecker from isobutyraldehyde should yield valinonitrile under the same mild conditions. DAP itself can form from wet-dry cycling of meteorite-derived phosphides (schreibersite). Phosphate minerals provide DAP precursor."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Valinonitrile hydrolysis to valine", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "acid or base catalysis; mineral surfaces optional", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild heating in acidic or basic aqueous solution; wet-dry cycling may assist"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (C\u2261N) of valinonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first, water attacks the nitrile carbon to form an amide intermediate (valinamide), which then hydrolyzes further to valine + NH3 (or valine under acidic conditions). The overall transformation: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COOH + NH3.", "reasoning": "Nitrile hydrolysis is the terminal step in all Strecker-based valine syntheses. Patel et al. (2015) and Miller & Schlesinger (1993) both invoke this step. Nitrile hydrolysis is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds spontaneously in warm aqueous solutions, especially under acidic or basic conditions. Geothermal heating (50-100\u00b0C) would accelerate this reaction in prebiotic pools."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Cyanohydrin hydrolysis of isobutyraldehyde cyanohydrin to alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "acid or base catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "isobutyraldehyde + HCN form cyanohydrin in situ, which hydrolyzes to \u03b1-hydroxy acid; two-step one-pot process"}, "mechanism": "Isobutyraldehyde reacts with HCN to form cyanohydrin (identical to compound 26 from Patel pathway). Under acidic or basic aqueous conditions, the nitrile group of this cyanohydrin hydrolyzes (via amide intermediate) to the carboxylic acid, yielding 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanoic acid (\u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid). The \u03b1-OH is retained (unlike the Strecker route where NH3 replaces OH).", "reasoning": "Cyanohydrin formation + hydrolysis is the classical route to \u03b1-hydroxy acids, directly paralleling the Strecker route but without NH3. Kaur et al. (2024) noted that \u03b1-hydroxy acids are co-products of reductive amination alongside amino acids, confirming this competing pathway. This provides a prebiotic route to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid, the immediate precursor to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via oxidation."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Oxidation of alpha-hydroxyisovaleric acid to alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photocatalysis on TiO2; Fe3+ ions from pyrite weathering", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, mild oxidation; Fe3+ acts as one-electron oxidant"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-hydroxyl group of \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid is oxidized to a ketone, yielding \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid). This can proceed via UV-TiO2 photocatalytic oxidation (generating hydroxyl radicals that selectively abstract the \u03b1-H) or by Fe3+-mediated electron transfer (Fe3+ \u2192 Fe2+ + radical, followed by radical recombination to give the ketone).", "reasoning": "\u03b1-Hydroxy acid to \u03b1-keto acid oxidation is thermodynamically favorable and can be driven by UV photochemistry or Fe3+ oxidation. This provides a prebiotically plausible route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, which Kaur et al. (2024) used as the starting material for reductive amination. The prebiotic source of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is identified as a key open question in the literature; this cyanohydrin hydrolysis \u2192 oxidation route addresses that gap using isobutyraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)9S8)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-370K", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe sulfide minerals (pentlandite)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-8, NH4HCO3 buffer (150 mM), 72h reaction time; Ni-bearing meteorite powder also effective"}, "mechanism": "H2 dissociatively adsorbs on Ni-containing mineral surfaces, generating metal-hydride species. The \u03b1-keto acid (\u03b1-ketoisovalerate) first forms an imine with NH3 (via condensation of the ketone with ammonia), then the metal-hydride reduces the C=N imine bond to give the amino acid (valine). Competing \u03b1-hydroxy acid formation occurs via direct C=O reduction without NH3.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024, Chem) demonstrated this reaction explicitly: Ni nanoparticles or FeNi meteorite powder catalyzed H2-driven conversion of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate to valine at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 5 bar H2. Combined amino + hydroxy acid yields were 6-84% depending on catalyst (Ni gave ~50%). Pd gave 80-90% yield with >5:1 amino:hydroxy selectivity. No reaction occurred without metal catalyst. Natural analogs include pentlandite and awaruite (Ni3Fe) in alkaline hydrothermal vents."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on Ni catalyst", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pentlandite ((Fe,Ni)9S8)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-370K", "pressure": "5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni nanoparticles or Ni-Fe minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-8, NH4HCO3, analogous conditions to rxn_017"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate condenses with NH3 to form an imine, which is reduced by H2 on Ni surface to give alanine. Identical mechanism to rxn_017 but with the C3 substrate pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated reductive amination of multiple \u03b1-keto acids including pyruvate to the corresponding amino acids. Alanine production from pyruvate is well-established in this system. Alanine serves as an amino group donor for transamination reactions downstream."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Metal-catalyzed transamination: alpha-ketoisovalerate + alanine to valine + pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_023", "mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+/Cu2+ ions as Lewis acid catalysts", "aqueous": true, "other": "requires metal-ion catalysis for prebiotic transamination; Fe2+ abundant on early Earth; may occur at mineral-water interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Alanine forms a Schiff base with \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (or with a metal-bound pyridoxal analog). The amino group is transferred from alanine to the keto acid via a tautomeric shift through the ketimine-aldimine equilibrium, yielding valine + pyruvate. Fe2+ or Cu2+ coordinates both substrates and lowers the activation barrier for the 1,3-prototropic shift.", "reasoning": "Transamination is the biological route to valine (via branched-chain aminotransferase). Prebiotic transamination has been demonstrated with metal-ion catalysts (Fe2+, Cu2+) substituting for pyridoxal phosphate. Miller & Schlesinger (1993) noted that metal salts catalyze \u03b1-ketoisovalerate reactions. This pathway regenerates pyruvate, creating a proto-metabolic cycle. While less efficient than enzymatic transamination, it provides an alternative route to valine when \u03b1-ketoisovalerate and alanine co-occur."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite surface catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent, multiple CO2 reduction steps on mineral surface"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction on iron oxide/sulfide surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde (via surface-bound intermediates) \u2192 pyruvate via further carboxylation and oxidation. The mineral surface provides a template for stepwise carbon fixation, analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 + H2 on iron mineral surfaces has been demonstrated experimentally. Magnetite and greigite catalyze these multi-step reductions at alkaline vent conditions. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub in both biology and prebiotic chemistry. It serves as both a precursor to alanine (via rxn_018) and a transamination product (rxn_019)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Miller-Urey spark discharge synthesis of valine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "800-1200K (brief spark), then 300K (cooling)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "electric discharge (lightning analog); mineral dust (TiO2) may serve as nucleation surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "reducing atmosphere: CH4 + NH3 + H2O + H2; spark produces HCN, aldehydes, which undergo Strecker-type chemistry upon cooling and dissolution in water"}, "mechanism": "Electric discharge through a reducing gas mixture (CH4, NH3, H2O, H2) fragments molecules into reactive radicals (CH, CH2, NH, CN). Upon cooling, these recombine to form HCN, aldehydes (including trace isobutyraldehyde), and NH3. In the aqueous phase, Strecker-type chemistry converts these to aminonitriles, which hydrolyze to amino acids. Valine is a minor product alongside dominant glycine and alanine.", "reasoning": "Johnson et al. (2009) reanalyzed Miller's original 1953 spark-discharge samples and detected valine and isovaline among ~40 amino acids. While valine is only a trace product (glycine/alanine dominate), its presence confirms that branched amino acids can arise from simple reducing gas mixtures under spark-discharge conditions. This represents an atmospheric/lightning route to valine."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Atmospheric HCN synthesis from methane and nitrogen", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "800-1200K (lightning/UV), 300K (ambient)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photolysis or electrical discharge", "aqueous": false, "other": "atmospheric chemistry; CH4 + N sources (NH3, N2) \u2192 HCN via radical reactions; HCN dissolves in rain and accumulates in surface pools"}, "mechanism": "UV photolysis or lightning discharge fragments CH4 into CH and CH2 radicals, and NH3 into NH radicals. CH + NH recombine to form HCN. Alternatively, N2 + CH4 under strong UV or discharge yields HCN directly. HCN accumulates in the atmosphere and dissolves in rainwater, concentrating in surface pools and lakes.", "reasoning": "Atmospheric HCN production is a well-established source of prebiotic cyanide. HCN is the critical C1/N building block for both Strecker synthesis and cyanosulfidic chemistry. Miller-Urey experiments demonstrate HCN as a primary product of spark discharge (Johnson et al., 2009). HCN dissolved in surface water feeds into all downstream cyanide-dependent pathways."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full Patel cyanosulfidic pathway (formose to valine)", "description": "Complete cyanosulfidic route starting from formaldehyde through formose chemistry to glyceraldehyde, then photoreduction to acetone, followed by Patel et al.'s (2015) four-step homologation to valinonitrile, ending with hydrolysis to valine. This is the most experimentally validated prebiotic pathway to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_016", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 to cyanosulfidic valine (cross-environment)", "description": "Starting from hydrothermal CO2 fixation to formate, then surface photoreduction to formaldehyde, entering the formose/cyanosulfidic cascade to valine. Demonstrates Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanosulfidic isobutyraldehyde to classical Strecker", "description": "Cyanosulfidic pathway generates cyanohydrin 26, which undergoes reversible dissociation to release free isobutyraldehyde. This aldehyde then enters classical Strecker synthesis (isobutyraldehyde + NH3 + HCN \u2192 valinonitrile \u2192 valine). Connects Patel photochemistry with Miller-Schlesinger Strecker route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "DAP-mediated Strecker at neutral pH", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde (from cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin dissociation) undergoes Strecker synthesis at neutral pH mediated by diamidophosphate (DAP), as demonstrated by Powner et al. (2019). This route overcomes the pH constraint of classical Strecker (which needs pH > 9 for free NH3).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_016", "mol_017", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Kaur reductive amination from cyanosulfidic \u03b1-ketoisovalerate", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic pathway is converted to \u03b1-hydroxyisovaleric acid (via cyanohydrin hydrolysis), then oxidized to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, and finally reduced to valine by H2 on Ni minerals. This connects Patel's surface chemistry to Kaur et al.'s hydrothermal reductive amination.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_017", "mol_020", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination (shortest from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate)", "description": "Direct reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with H2 and NH3 on Ni catalyst, as demonstrated by Kaur et al. (2024). This is the most direct route when \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is available, requiring only one reaction step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Transamination pathway via alanine", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis, followed by reductive amination to alanine (on Ni), then metal-catalyzed transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate with alanine to yield valine + pyruvate. This creates a proto-metabolic autocatalytic cycle where pyruvate is regenerated.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_020", "rxn_018", "rxn_016", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_022", "mol_021", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Full cross-environment transamination (Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical)", "description": "CO2 is fixed to pyruvate hydrothermally; pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine. In parallel, the cyanosulfidic surface pathway generates isobutyraldehyde, which is converted to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate via cyanohydrin hydrolysis and oxidation. Alanine and \u03b1-ketoisovalerate then undergo transamination to valine in the biochemical regime.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_020", "rxn_018", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_022", "mol_021", "mol_013", "mol_017", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Miller-U