her reactions and lacks mineral catalyst specification. The UV photoreduction of formate to formaldehyde, while thermodynamically feasible, has limited prebiotic literature support. The rest of the pathway inherits the strengths of P1.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Replace rxn_002 with a better-documented route to formaldehyde, e.g., Cannizzaro reaction or direct hydrothermal reduction\", \"Specify mineral photocatalyst (e.g., TiO2 or ZnS) for formate photoreduction\", \"Consider atmospheric formaldehyde production as alternative entry point\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"Clever convergent route using cyanosulfidic chemistry to generate isobutyraldehyde (via cyanohydrin 26 dissociation), then classical Strecker. The cyanohydrin dissociation (rxn_011) is thermodynamically reasonable and provides a prebiotic source of isobutyraldehyde \u2014 directly addressing the open challenge noted in literature. The Strecker step (rxn_012) is highly literature-validated. However, the pathway stays entirely in the Surface environment, missing the cross-environment progression ideal.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Quantify the equilibrium of cyanohydrin dissociation \u2014 at what pH/conditions does this favor isobutyraldehyde release?\", \"Add Zn2+ or mineral catalyst for the Strecker imine formation step\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_s